<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss President Rejects Jewish Demand for Creation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Swiss President Jean-Pascal
Delamuraz has rejected the demand for the creation of a
compensation fund of 250 million francs (about 200 U.S. dollars)
for Nazi victims during World War Two, said local press reports
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Swiss reporters Monday, Delamuraz said
that the creation of a compensation fund is not a good idea, which
could make the investigation of the alleged Jewish assets in Swiss
banks more difficult. He denounced the demand as "no less than
ransom and chantage."
</P>
<P>
"What should be done now is to have the facts come to light
rapidly and, especially, clearly," said Delamuraz. He said that an
investigation commission of experts established recently should
deal with issues concerning the alleged Jewish assets in
Switzerland before a conclusion is made.
</P>
<P>
According to the Swiss press, Jewish groups have asked the
Swiss government to set up a compensation fund during the
investigation, which is due to last three to five years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Swiss Ambassador to the United States Thomas Borer,
head of a fact-finding task force of Jewish assets in Switzerland,
announced that Switzerland might set up a compensation fund in
1997.
</P>
<P>
However, Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti said on December
23 that he was opposed to the creation of the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
