<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Variety of Celebrations Staged in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A variety of New Year
celebrations were held throughout the territory to greet 1997,
attracting tens of thousands of Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's returning to her motherland July 1, 1997 has cast a
special glamour to the New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
At the Victoria Park on Hong Kong Island, a family fun carnival
organized by the Urban Council was started at 20:30 to greet 1997,
featuring both spectator programs and participatory activities for
all age groups.
</P>
<P>
Highlight of the evening began at 23:50, when guests joined
performers at different stages to cheer the countdown to 1997 in
the dying seconds of the old year.
</P>
<P>
The four-hour exciting programs included a thrilling but funny
acrobatic show by Bobarino Gravittini from America; "Dance into
97" by the City Contemporary Dance Company; Middle-Eastern and
Hawaiian dances; popular Chinese music by the Hong Kong Chinese
Orchestra; Latin American music and rock jazz performances; and
live shows by Radio Television Hong Kong and Cable TV.
</P>
<P>
Participatory activities included an outdoor disco for
youngsters to dance from indoor to outdoor, a grand ballroom dance
tent for dance lovers, "Children's Fun Corner", handicraft
workshops, games, booths, inflatables, "Bubble Forest" as well as
street entertainment from clowns, jugglers, stilt-walkers and
balloon-twisters.
</P>
<P>
Tuen Mun in the New Territories ushered in the new year in a
more spectacular way, by giving the largest ever fireworks display
in Hong Kong's history off the Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
China-made fireworks were launched from the sea around midnight
and the whole display lasted for 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizer for the fireworks display, an
estimated 200,000 local people flocked to the seaside to enjoy a
colorful New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
All the rooms, together with the seats in the dining halls, in
the Gold Coast Hotel which has a good view of the display, had
been booked for the night, Zuky Wo, assistant director of sales
for the hotel, said.
</P>
<P>
At Times Square in Causeway Bay, a cheerful countdown gathering
hosted by local singers was staged from 22:30 and climaxed when
the clock struck 24:00.
</P>
<P>
At Tsim Sha Tsui, the southern tip of Kowloon, jubilant people
gathered under a huge clock in the open air, waiting for the
exciting moment.
</P>
<P>
At Central's Lan Kwi Fong street, featured by a bunch of
westernized pubs and discos, foreigners living in Hong Kong were
celebrating the coming of the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
