<HEADLINE> Liberation Army Daily On Stationing Troops In Hong Kong Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Law on Stationing
Troops in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), or
Garrison Law will ensure that the troops perform their duties
well, a commentator's article in today's Liberation Army Daily
says.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, the troops will go to station in Hong Kong to take
charge of the special administrative region's defense duty, which
"will be an important indication that China is resuming the
exercise of its sovereign over Hong Kong and put an end to the
rule of Britain in Hong Kong," the artile said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the "one country, two systems" policy, the
law explicitly defines the duties of the PLA troops to be
stationed in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
What image the troops will present to Hong Kong society is
matter of concern to the Party Central Committee, the State
Council and the Central Military Commission on one hand and the
residents of Hong Kong on the other.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Garrison Law has set strict demands on the tasks
and disciplines for the men of the stationed troops. And they are
expected to abide not only by national laws and army disciplines,
but also by the laws of the HK SAR, the commentator articles says.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the article says, the stationed troops should respect
Hong Kong's social system and way of life, and protect public
assets and personal property. And on no account, are they allowed
to engage in profit-making business or other activities that are
incompatible with the status of armymen.
</P>
<P>
The article goes on to note that the Garrison Law is the norm
of standards formulated by the state for the troops to be
stationed in Hong Kong to follow in carrying out various
activities,
</P>
<P>
The article prompts the troops and other military personnel to
acquaint themselves with the Garrison Law and prepare themselves
for its implementation.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the troops to be stationed in Hong Kong,
who have undergone rigid education and formal training giving them
top-notch qualifications, will carry out their duties in strict
accordance with the law after they go to station in Hong Kong on
July 1, 1997, and prove themselves to be a army worthy of both
might and hight moral standards," the commentator's article says.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
