<HEADLINE> UK House Prices Set to Increase 7-8 Pct in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- House prices in Britain are set
to increase by 7 or 8 percent in 1997-1998 as the country moves
towards a steadier housing market reminiscent of the 1960s,
according to a report of Britain's largest building society,
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax forecast, in line with those of the other major
building societies, such as the Nationwide and Abbey National,
will help to cheer the government over the new year as it seeks to
foster a "feelgood factor" in the run-up to the general election
due to be held next May, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax report stressed that the recovery should neither
run out of control, as in the late 1980s, nor be derailed by a
"moderate" rise in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"We do not forecast a boom that has to be halted by much
sharper rises in interest rates. A return to the steadier housing
market growth of the 1960s rather than the sharp fluctuations of
the past 25 years is a distinct possibility," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed out that the only danger was that too
strong a recovery would prompt higher interest rates or a further
withdrawal of tax relief on mortgages after an election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
