<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US New Home Sales Up Sharply in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S.
shot up by 14.2 percent in November, the largest advance in more
than three years, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that sales of single-family homes totaled a
seasonally adjusted 772,000 annual rate, up sharply from the sale
in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The department also revised down the sales in October to
676,000 from the initially estimated figure of 714,000. The
decrease pushed the sales rate below 700,000 for the first time in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The new home sales in November were the highest level since an
820,000 rate in August and the biggest increase since sales rose
by 16.6 percent in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, sales of new homes in the U.S. were 13.2
percent above those in the first 11 months of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The big jump in new home sales resulted mainly from lower
mortgages in the country. The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. has
reported that 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 7.62 percent
in November, down from 7.85 percent in October and 8.32 percent as
recently as last June.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales increased by 40.3 percent in Northeast, the
largest since sales rose 67.4 percent in December 1995. They rose
by 16 percent in the Midwest and 11.5 percent in the West. The
sales were up by 10.2 percent in the South, the largest gain since
sales increased 28.7 percent in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
The housing industry has been a major source of strength during
the six-year economic expansion in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Association of Realtors also reported Monday
that sales of existing homes increased by 1.8 percent in November,
reversing a five-month string of declines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
