<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Embassy in Nigeria Cancels New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Embassy in Nigeria
has cancelled its annual New Year party for its citizens living
in Nigeria following the hostage saga in the Japanese embassy
in Peru.
</P>
<P>
An embassy spokesman announced the cancellation, saying it had
received an order from Tokyo against "circumstances beyond our
control."
</P>
<P>
But analysts here said it might be connected with fear for
insecurity. Armed leftists rebels of Peru's Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement stormed the residence of the Japanese
ambassador in Peru on December 17 during a reception marking
Emperor Akihito's birthday and seized more than 650 hostages.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have so far released 570 of the hostages while
negotiations are still going on to free the rest.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria, there are about 100
Japanese residing in Nigeria. They usually perform rituals
associated with Japanese Shinto religion and Buddhism at the New
Year party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
