<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Quits COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Cooperation, Leonardo Simao, confirmed here today
that his country has withdrawn from the Common Market of the
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
"It is in our interest that we engage ourselves in the
cooperation with Southern African Development Community (SADC)
instead of joining the COMESA, an organisation with more members
and more problems," said Simao.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Mozambique had merely signed an agreement to
join COMESA, but had never ratified the membership.
</P>
<P>
"it is our experience that the smaller the organisation is,
the better it can function, because in that case it would be more
convenient for its members to communicate and compromise with
each other," he said, referring to the SADC.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not saying that there is a danger of break-up for COMESA.
I'm just saying that Mozambique is not interested in joining it,"
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Simao added that apart from doing business with SADC, his
country is also tapping potentials for closer business ties with
Southeast Asia and the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croats Accuse Muslims of Checking Refugee Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior Bosnian Croat
official today blamed the Muslims for obstructing the return of
130,000 Croat refugees to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) leader in Bosnia Bozo
Rajic said in a new year message to the Croats that the
Muslim-Croat Federation would not work unless all banished Croats
return to Muslim-controlled areas next year.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Muslims and Croats formed the federation in March
of 1994 under the sponsorship of the United States. But due to
different national interests, the federation has failed to work
smoothly so far.
</P>
<P>
Rajic said the Croat side demanded that refugees of the
federation be repatriated in line with the principle of "all for
all," while Muslims asked for the refugee return on a "one for
one" basis.
</P>
<P>
If the Muslims' proposal is accepted, then 130,000 Croats will
not be able to return home because about 180,000 Croats have been
expelled from Muslim-controlled areas while 50,000 Muslims from
the Croat community of Herzeg-Bosna, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the areas where Croat refugees should return,
Rajic included parts of the municipalities of Bugojno, Travnik,
Vares, Kakanj, and Zenica in central Bosnia-Herzegovina among the
"historical" Croat lands.
</P>
<P>
Even if the Croats could return to these areas, however, the
situation would still be difficult for them as the Muslims were
against the new Croat municipalities with full local
self-administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
