<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Pledges to Facilitate Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides pledged here today that he will do all he can to
facilitate the peace efforts toward a solution to the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
The president made the pledge in his new year message. However,
he said that he is not prepared to make any concessions that
would not secure the future of coming generations on the island.
</P>
<P>
"Any solution should secure the fundamental freedoms and
human rights, rid Cyprus of the Turkish occupation troops and
settlers and create such conditions, within the context of a
workable constitution, which would allow Greek Cypriots, Turkish
Cypriots, Armenians, Latins and Maronites to live together on
the island," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
and took control of the northern third of the island following
a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The problem has remained unsolved despite all the U.N. and
international peace efforts for the past 22 years.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, President Clerides reaffirmed today
that the republic's arms acquisition program will not be modified
regardless of any threats.
</P>
<P>
"I give you my word of honor, as Glafcos Clerides, as
President of the Republic of Cyprus and as a Cypriot, that
we shall not, no matter what the threat, alter the arms
purchasing program which we believe to be essential for our
defense," the president said during a visit to National Guard
posts along the demarcation line.
</P>
<P>
The resident referred to the statements by Turkish officials
that Turkey will not remain silent in the face of the Greek
Cypriot side's purchasing of arms of offensive nature.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has purchased tanks and armored vehicles from Russia
and now is negotiating a deal with Russians to buy anti-aircraft
missile system S-300. 
</P>
</TEXT>
