<HEADLINE> 2 Islamic Militants Killed in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Two leading Islamic militants
suspected of a string of robberies and assaults were killed in a
shootout with state security police Tuesday in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
An official source at the Ministry of Interior said the two
men, identified as Saleh Mahmoud Saleh and Hassan Abdel Mawla,
were killed near the town of Adwa, Minya, 220 kilometers south of
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
A machinegun, a local-made rifle, a sum of money and ammunition
were found with the two militants, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The source said the two persons were detected as carrying
machineguns in a bag by the security police, who laid an ambush as
part of the operation in hot pursuit of militants across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The two militants, believed to be local leaders of the
outlawed Jamaa Islamiya, or the Islamic Group, were involved in a
number of robberies and attacks.
</P>
<P>
They killed the owner of a jewellry shop in a forced break-in
and robbed the Bank of Agricultural Development and Credit in a
village in Minya and injured the bank manager.
</P>
<P>
They also attacked the chief officer at Kahk police station in
Fayoum, 90 kilometers southwest of Cairo, and killed eight civilians
during the assault.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they were charged of assaults on the Banque Misr
branch in Giza and the rest house of police officers, the interior
ministry source said.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian police, which are targeted by the waves of violence,
have tightened security in southern Egypt where terrorist attacks
by suspected Moslem militants have broke out almost on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
The militants have waged a violent campaign against the
government since 1992 in an attempt to install Islamic rule in
Egypt. More than 1,035 people have died in the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
