<HEADLINE> Arafat: PA Ready to Initial Agreement on Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat said today he was ready to
initial the agreement on Israeli army's redeployment in the West
Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who has been blamed by the Israelis for delaying the
negotiations on the Hebron redeployment, made the remarks in
Gaza, as the negotiations continued in Jerusalem to finalize the
details of the accord.
</P>
<P>
However, the summit meeting between Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Arafat, scheduled to open tonight at the
Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip to close the
deal, is likely to be held Wednesday to allow Netanyahu to
take part in the 1997 budget debate in the Knesset (Israel's
parliament).
</P>
<P>
A Marathon Debate on the budget has been held in the Knesset
plenum throughout the day, and will be resumed in the evening
again before the deadline at 6 a.m. local time (0400GMT)
Wednesday when the budget should be passed and made into law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, negotiators from both sides said that almost all
issues have been resolved with U.S. special Middle East
coordinator Dennis Ross, who arrived here Monday in a continued
shuttling between Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Ross met Netanyahu again this afternoon, with the
participation of the Israeli negotiating team who took part in
today's talks with the Palestinians, held in a hotel in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Ross and the negotiators left the hotel to
continue the discussions, before the U.S. envoy's scheduled travel
to the Gaza Strip again this evening to meet with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's office said after the Netanyahu-Ross
meeting this afternoon that "as up to now there is no summit
meeting schedule between the Israeli prime minister and Arafat
either for tonight, or for tomorrow." 
</P>
