<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia to Normalize Ties With World Financial Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Minister Without
Portfolio Vuk Ognjanovic said today that 1997 would be marked by
the normalization of relations between Belgrade and international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the new year edition of the Belgrade
economic daily Privredni Pregled, Ognjanovic said the admission of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to the World Trade Organization
(WTO) was also the country's major task.
</P>
<P>
"Economic preconditions and conditions were created in which
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) should and could have acted
differently, and not postponed the full normalization of
relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We really did everything that was...within the powers of the
federal institutions for relations with international financial
and trade organizations to be normalized," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
After the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia in 1991, the
rump Yugoslavia has so far failed to be admitted into the United
Nations and many other key international financial institutions,
such as the IMF and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"With the suspension and then the lifting of the sanctions, the
political reasons which the IMF usually gave practically ceased to
exist," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
On December 14, the IMF's board of directors extended for
another six months the deadline within which Yugoslavia should
regulate its membership with this institution. The IMF said the
membership would not be considered unless Yugoslavia had given up
its condition of the exclusive continuity with the former
federation of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"By postponing the deadline for the normalization of relations,
the IMF has inflicted serious damage to our country, because other
partners thus also partly suspended their activities and put off
the closure of the talks," Ognjanovic said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said talks with the London Club and at the World
Bank were expected in the second half of January since its
technical mission, which recently visited Belgrade, gave a good
report on what Yugoslavia was offering and asking at this time.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is eager to join the international financial
organizations so as to get a large sum of loans and aid to revive
its economy which was devastated during the four-year-long
sanctions that were formally ended only three months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
