the Ethio-Djibouti Railway Company.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the 23rd Regular Meeting of the
Ethio-Djibouti Railway Company's Administative Council, Abdulmejid
said the new organizational structure will enable the company to
correct its shortcomings and become efficient and profitable.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the company which has served as a
significant economic tool for both countries during the past 90
years, registered poor performances for dozens of years,
due to obsolete machineries.
</P>
<P>
Abdulmejid said a study of the new organizational structure of
the company was conducted by experts drawn from Ethiopia and Djibouti
and included all the possible proposals for the improvement of the
company.
</P>
<P>
The study indicated that obsolete rails, locomotives and a
century old communication systems should be replaced by modern and
new ones to bring the company to efficiency and profitablity, the
Ethiopian minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the European Union, the Kuwait Fund, the World Bank and
the governments of France, Germany and Switzerland have expressed
readiness to give assistance for the improvement of the company in
line with the new study.
</P>
<P>
He added that six new locomotives will be acquired in six
months in a bid to increase the cargo capacity of the company and
measures are to be taken to improve its communication infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The 781-km Ethio-Djibouti railway was built at the beginning of
this century and administrated by both Ethiopian and Djiboutian
governments. enditem

