<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Cyprus Issue: Stalemate in 1996, Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.N.-proposed package includes unmanning of the areas
where the two sides are at close proximity with each other, the
prohibition of loaded weapons along the cease-fire line and the
code of conduct for the military along the cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official has expressed optimism that an agreement
will be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
The intensive international peace moves on Cyprus also
included the visit of the representative of the Irish presidency
of the European Union (EU), Kester Heaslip.
</P>
<P>
Heaslip expected that direct talks between the leaders of the
two communities for a Cyprus settlement will begin by March next
year, and hoped a solution to the Cyprus problem would be reached
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
His expectation was echoed by British Foreign Secretary
Malcolm Rifkind, who paid a two-day official visit to the island
this month, during which he had separate talks with Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Rifkind put forward a 10-point proposal, which he hopes
President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash will turn
into the provisions of a detailed settlement.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that before the end of the first half of 1997,
there should be an open-ended session of face-to-face
negotiations between the two sides under the aegis of the U.N.,
and hoped that both leaders will work whole-heartedly and
energetically for a settlement in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Rifkind also reiterated his position that he favored Cyprus-EU
membership talks to be conducted after a federation is
established, the view which has been criticized by Cypriot
politicians on the island.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided last year that accession talks with Cyprus
will start six months after the end of the EU Intergovernmental
Conference.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here noted that some EU members have used
the EU accession talks as a pressure on the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides to reach an early settlement.
</P>
<P>
However, the gap between the two sides has remained wide on
the main aspects of the Cyprus problem, with focus on security of
the two communities, guarantees, the issue of EU accession,
territorial and constitutional matters.
</P>
<P>
Both President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash,
however, have emphasised that "1997 is the year of opportunity."
</P>
<P>
There are signs that there is a change in the attitude of the
two communities' leaders toward their desirability of having
face-to-face negotiations in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
If this happens, it will be the first direct negotiations
between the two leaders since May 1993 when President Clerides and
Denktash met under the U.N. auspices in New York.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and seized the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks, aimed at reuniting the island
under a bizonal and bicommunal federal state, have been held on
and off for the past 22 years, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the task facing Cyprus in 1997
should not be underestimated, there is a prospect of direct
negotiation between the two sides; and in the event of this, a
major step will be taken toward a comprehensive settlement of the
protracted Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
