<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-31 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Mideast-North Africa Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Although the economic
cooperation between the Middle East and north African nations,
launched at the first Mideast-North Africa Economic Summit two
years ago, greatly backslided in 1996, the blue-print of the
scheme is still kept there to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The third Mideast-North Africa Economic Conference held in the
Egyptian capital of Cairo in November has saved the process of
economic cooperation from collapse and kept alive the wish of the
regional states to shape another economic block for much better
status in the international rivalry in the future.
</P>
<P>
The first Mideast-North Africa Economic Summit convened in the
Moroccan city of Casablanca in November 1994 set forth the idea
of economic cooperation between foes and allies alike in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The concept, which for the first time was welcomed and
supported not only by Arab nations and Israel but also by the
international community, was developed at the second summit in
the Jordanian capital of Amman in November 1995. At the Amman
summit, concrete rules and norms were worked out, thus building
an atmosphere of trust that geared up the momentum.
</P>
<P>
At the Casablanca summit, leaders of most Arab countries and
Israel gathered under the same roof for the first time to discuss
ways of promoting economic cooperation between the Middle East
and north African nations.
</P>
<P>
It led to the withdrawal or halt of the boycott of Israel by
Arab states, turning foes into partners after half a decade of
enmity.
</P>
<P>
At the Amman summit, it was agreed to establish a
Mideast-north Africa development bank, a regional council of
businessmen and a regional tourism council. Since then
encouraging signs of regional economic cooperation, including
Arab-Israeli economic cooperation, have emerged.
</P>
<P>
But the Likud government of Israel headed by Binyamin
Netanyahu who came into power in May 1996 has adopted a chain of
hardline policies that blocked the Middle East peace process and
are greatly detrimental to the momentum of regional economic
cooperation gained at the first summit.
</P>
<P>
Although the third Mideast-North Africa Economic Conference
was convened on schedule and the regional nations do cherish the
idea of collective action, the prospects of economic cooperation
between the Middle East and north-African nations in the
foreseeable future are not much encouraging because of
difficulties lying ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-31 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Mideast-North Africa Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The first difficulty is the lack of political guarantee as
Arab-Israeli relations have receded.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu came into power,
he declared "three No's", announcing that Israel would not
withdraw from the occupied Syrian Golan Heights, would not allow
Jerusalem to be partitioned and would not agree to setting up an
independent Palestinian state. He even threatened to cancel the
Oslo accords reached by Israel with the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) in 1993. Hence the Middle East peace process
was once again stumbled.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's actions have triggered a wave of indignation and
condemnation from Arab countries and spoiled the favorable
atmosphere for further Arab-Israeli cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The second difficulty facing economic cooperation between the
Middle East and north-African nations is that inter-Arab economic
cooperation has its own obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Facts have shown that it is easy to talk about Arab-Arab
cooperation while it is difficult to translate such cooperation
into a reality.
</P>
<P>
The third problem is the failure to establish three
already-declared institutions.
</P>
<P>
Both the Casablanca and Amman economic summits called for
establishing a Mideast-north Africa development bank, a regional
council of businessmen and a regional tourism council. But the
Cairo conference failed to set dates for the establishment of
those institutions.
</P>
<P>
The fourth problem is the lack of infrastructure. It is
estimated that investments needed for infrastructure projects in
the Middle East and north Africa amount to 350 billion
U.S. dollars during the period from 1997 to 2006, a sum
impossible to raise by the countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East and north Africa, with an area of more than 15
million square kilometers and a population of 300 million, have
great potentials for economic development, but the blueprint
approved by the three conferences can be turned into a reality
only after real peace prevails in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-31 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain Welcomes Qatari Decision to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain today expressed
appreciation of Qatar's decision to return a Bahraini military
helicopter which landed at Doha airport Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bahrain demanded that Nasser Majid Nasser al
Khalifa, the Bahraini pilot who flew the helicopter and asked for
political asylum in Qatar, be handed over to the Bahraini
authorities at the earliest possible time.
</P>
<P>
A statement to this effect was made today by Bahraini
Information Minister Mohammad al-Muttawa to the Gulf news agency.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in his statement that the pilot was not
banned from going abroad, and could go to any other country
whenever he wished.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari government decided to return the military plane to
Bahrein, while granting asylum to the pilot and giving him the
freedom of choice whether to stay on in Qatar or to return to the
Bahraini capital of Manama, or to go to anywhere else he wants.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari news agency quoted a Qatari Foreign Ministry source
as saying earlier today that Qatar had sent an official note to
the Bahraini Foreign Ministry in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The source noted that Qatar, taking into account the existing
fraternal relations between the two countries and peoples, decided
to return the military plane to Bahrain, while granting political
asylum to the pilot.
</P>
<P>
Both Bahrain and Qatar are members of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC), but they have a territorial dispute that has led to
Bahrain's boycott of the GCC summit convened in the Qatari capital
of Doha on December 7-9. This was the first such incident since
the GCC's foundation in 1981. 
</P>
