<HEADLINE> Arafat-Netanyahu Summit Due to Seal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A summit between Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat will be held Wednesday to seal the Hebron deal, Israel
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that the Arafat-Netanyahu summit will be held
Wednesday afternoon at the Erez checkpoint between Israel and
the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the summit would have taken place today in
 order to meet the new year deadline, but Netanyahu was too busy
in the Knesset (Parliament) to make this schedule, Netanyahu's
spokesman Shai Bazak was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset is holding heated debate, which will last till
early Wednesday morning, on passing the 1997 budget, which
Netanyahu wanted to see it passed before going to deal with the
Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strong opposition even within his coalition,
Netanyahu wanted to make sure that his coaliation partners would
support the budget to avoid a possible government crisis. The
budget, which is to cut 7 billion shekels (2.3 billion dollars),
has aroused strong protests from various walks of life in the
Jewish states.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross held a meeting
with Netanyahu but failed to fix the summit for late today as
was predicted by local media.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who returned to the region Monday, held separate
meetings with Netanyahu and Arafat Monday night to bridge the
remaining gap between the two sides. Arafat said he was willing
to hold a meeting with Netanyahu later today to wrap up the
long-delayed deal on the Israeli troop redeployment in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said the Hebron agreement had in fact been
completed and was only waiting for the two leaders'
signature. Until today, the two sides were said to be split over
the issues of conducting joint police patrols near the Tomb of
Patriachs in Hebron and the timetable for Israeli troop's further
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side insisted on the demand for joint patrols
near the Tomb of Patriachs, the religious shrine holy to both
Jews and Moslems. But Netanyahu rejected such demand, saying
Israel would retain sole security control in the area to protect
the holy site and the safety of 450 settlers living among
200,000 Palestinians in the city.
</P>
<P>
If the Hebron deal is signed, it will be the first
breakthrough in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process which has
been virtually stalled since Israel's hardline Likud government
took power in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
