<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Cyprus Issue: Stalemate in 1996, Hope for Progress in 1997 (I) (By Huang Jianming) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The year 1996 witnessed
another stalemate in the intermittent efforts to solve the
country's problem and ease tension along the 180-kilometer-long
buffer zone across this East Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Parties involved, however, still hopes for a breakthrough in
working out a solution to the long-standing Cyprus problem in the
first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Greece and Turkey were once on the brink of
open hostilities over the sovereignty of uninhabited islets in the
Aegean, which affected the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The United States, who claimed to impose a solution to the
Cyprus problem in 1996, postponed its initiative due to the
killing of a Greek Cypriot and later the U.S. presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
In June, tension between the opposing forces were on the rise
after Greek Cypriot soldier Stelios Panagyi was shot dead when he
reportedly went to exchange hats with a Turkish Cypriot soldier
in the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. permanent representative to the U.N. Madeleine
Albright came to the island in July, brokering an agreement on a
meeting between commanders of the National Guard, the Cyprus armed
forces and Turkish forces in Cyprus. The move was aimed at
easing tension along the Green Line.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreement failed to take effect due to the Turkish
side's insistence that the commanders of Turkish Cypriot forces
also participate in the talks. The Turkish demand was rejected by
the Greek Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
In August, tension escalated again when some Greek Cypriots
demonstrated against the Turkish occupation near the
U.N.-controlled buffer zone, resulting in clashes between the two
sides and two unarmed Greek Cypriots were killed consequently.
</P>
<P>
Clashes intermittently plagued the island. Since June this
year, four Greek Cypriots have been killed and a Turkish soldier
mysteriously murdered in the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, both of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides
staged military exercises with the participation of Greek and
Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
The fatal incidents and military buildup on the island prompted
the U.N. and international community to intensify their peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali sent his
special representative for Cyprus Han Sung Joo to the island in a
bid to break the impasse and bring about early direct talks
between leaders of the two communities.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council also adopted a resolution in June,
expressing serious concern about the continued modernization and
upgrading of military forces in Cyprus, excessive levels of
military forces and armaments as well as lack of progress toward
a significant reduction in the number of foreign troops on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. auspices, an indirect military dialogue between
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides is now underway, with the aim to
ease tension along the cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. resident representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, the two sides have agreed to deal with the entire
package of measures which the U.N. suggested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
