<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-31 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Solution to Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The summit between Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat will be held Wednesday to seal the Hebron deal, Israel
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The long-delayed Hebron deal between the Israelis and
Palestinians will be the first major development since the
right-wing Israeli government assumed power last June as it would
pave the way for further progresses in negotiations between
Israel and Palestine and between Israel and other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interim Agreement, known as Oslo II, the
Israeli army was originally supposed to complete its redeployment
in the Hebron area by March 28.
</P>
<P>
However, following a series of suicide bombing attacks in
Israel last February and March, which left more than 60 people
dead and some 100 wounded, former Prime Minister Shimon Peres
delayed the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Peres, defeated by Likud Chairman Binyamin Netanyahu in the
elections on May 29, said afterward that he would leave the
decision of the redeployment to the new prime minister and his
government.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, some 30 kilometers southwest of Jerusalem, is a place
of pilgrimage for Christians, Jews and Moslems alike, and
tradition has it that patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob and their
wives are all buried in the Machpelah Cave (Haram al-Khalil, or
the Ibrahimi Mosque).
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, unique among the West Bank cities, Jews live side
by side with Palestinians, approximately 450 Jewish settlers
among 200,000 Arabs, which explains why until now Hebron remains
the only major West Bank town still under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
Israel had completed its army's redeployment by the end of
last year in the other West Bank towns of Jenin, Tulkarm,
Kalkilya, Nablus, Ramallah and Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
The name "Hebron" is thought to come from the Hebrew HAVER
(friend), while in Arabic, the town is called Al-Khalil, with a
similar meaning, after Abraham (Ibrahim) "the friend of God."
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the city has been split into two, the north cut
off from the south by a series of roadblocks and check points set
up to secure the Jewish neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
In order to minimize friction between the Jewish and
Palestinian populations, the Israelis ordered the nearby market,
the now well-known Shuhada Street, and the bus station closed,
and extra security measures were introduced throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo II, 80 percent of Hebron is to be handed over
to the Palestinian Authority (PA), which will be able to deploy
400 uniformed policemen with 200 pistols and 100 assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 20 percent of the city, the eastern side that
includes the Jews, the Tomb of the Patriarchs, and about 12,000
Palestinians, will remain under Israeli control, as will the
roads linking the city to Kiryat Arba, home to 6,000 Jewish
settlers.
</P>
<P>
In October, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators started a new
round of continuous talks on the redeployment in Hebron, which
had already been delayed for more than half a year.
</P>
<P>
At the talks, Israel insisted on changes in the security
arrangements agreed upon under the Oslo accords, in light of the
violent confrontations between Israelis and Palestinians in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-31 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Solution to Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the confrontations, triggered by the opening of the
Hasmonean Tunnel by Israel in Jerusalem's Old City, more than 70
people were killed and hundreds of others wounded.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the confrontations, U.S. President Bill Clinton
called for an emergency summit in Washington to resuscitate the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
As one of the few results of the summit, Israel and Palestine
agreed to hold round-the-clock talks in an attempt to resolve
their differences on Hebron.
</P>
<P>
However, after four weeks of continuous talks, with the
participation of U.S. special Middle East coordinator Dennis
Ross, both sides failed to complete a deal.
</P>
<P>
In November, they once again tried to close the Hebron deal
through U.S. mediation, but failed at the last minute to work out
an agreement on the security arrangement and other related issues.
</P>
<P>
Israel media then reported that the main stumbling blocks
continued to be the right of "hot pursuit of terrorists" into
the Palestinian-ruled areas required by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel also requested reducing the number of individual
weapons Palestinian police would be carrying, insisting that the
Palestinian policemen should be armed with revolvers instead of
rifles as stipulated in Oslo II.
</P>
<P>
Clinton sent Ross to the region again in another effort to
help Israelis and Palestinians to narrow their differences over
the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
After two days of continuous shuttle, the U.S. envoy finally
brought Netanyahu and PA President Yasser Arafat together for a
summit meeting, the first between the two since the Washington
summit in October.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Netanyahu and Arafat made key
security-related "trade-offs" and instructed their negotiators to
accelerate work on details of a Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli senior officials revealed that under the "trade-offs,"
the Palestinians adhere to "perimeter zones" outside the Jewish
areas of Hebron, where restrictions on Palestinians using rifles
will prevent sniping at settlers.
</P>
<P>
In return, Israel will relinquish its insistence on explicit
language that would enable it to act preemptively against
potential attacks from the Palestinian controlled area.
</P>
<P>
The Hebron agreement is reportedly to be accompanied by a
U.S. document, currently entitled "Note for the Record," in which
"reciprocal" Palestinian obligations to Israel and Israeli
obligations to the Palestinians beyond Hebron will be spelled
out.
</P>
<P>
This document will also contain the date of the first Israeli
army pullback beyond Hebron, something mandated by Oslo II,
which is expected to occur in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected that the U.S. document will note other
unresolved issues, such as prisoner releases, establishment of
the Dahaniya airport in the Gaza Strip, implementing
safe-passage routes between the West Bank and Gaza, and further
easing of closure.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel is insisting that the Palestinians "first
and foremost" enumerate what parts of the PLO Covenant have been
abrogated, disarm Hamas, and reduce the number of Palestinian
policemen in accordance with ceilings set in Oslo II.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the Hebron redeployment would put the peace
process back on track, and pave the way for further progresses in
negotiations between Israel and Palestinians, and between Israel
and other Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
