<HEADLINE> Boutros-Ghali Bids Farewell to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Boutros Boutros-Ghali
on Tuesday bid farewell to the United Nations, whose term as the
head of the world body terminates in midnight today.
</P>
<P>
In walking out of the U.N. Secretariat Building accompanied by
his aids and security guards, he warmly shook hands with the staff
waiting in the main lobby.
</P>
<P>
"Thank you for everything you have done," said Boutros-Ghali to
reporters at the door. "Wish you a happy new year, wish success to
the United Nations, and wish success to my successor Koffi Annan."
</P>
<P>
Boutros-Ghali said he would continue to serve the United
Nations in different capacity, "among them an eminent person". He
will have a stop-over in Paris and then go to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He has been serving the world body for five years. His bid for
a second term was blocked by the United States, which blamed him
for lack of enthusiasm for the reform of the organization.
</P>
<P>
His successor, a Ghanaian citizen and a civil servant in the
United Nations, will take over the office tomorrow on January 1,
1997.  
