<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average dove 101 points today, sliding into the close of 1996
after some unexpectedly strong economic data.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 101.10 points to
6,448.27. It was the biggest one-day point drop since a 161-point
plunge on July's 15. But the famed barometer of 30 big U.S.
companies, now below 6,500-mark, still has a healthy 26 percent
gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,298 up, with volume reaching
395.15 million shares, as against 339.01 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 13.11 to 740.74,
leaving the widely watched index of large companies with a gain of
about 20.3 percent on the year.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index fell 35.13 to 392.29, ending 1996
with a 19.1 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 3.27 to 1,291.02, up 22.7
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange's market value index fell 0.18 to
583.28, up 6.4 percent on the year.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 list of smaller companies rose 2.62 to 362.61,
up 14.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market measures fell sharply too, ending a surprisingly
lucrative year on a discouraging note.
</P>
<P>
Stocks dropped with bonds after the Commerce Department said
new home sales shot up 14.2 percent to 772,000 in November, the
steepest advance in 3 years and more and fresh evidence the
housing industry continues to help drive the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, meanwhile, the Conference Board research
group said consumer confidence rose sharply to a seven-year high
in December, its second straight monthly increase.
</P>
<P>
The reports jostled widespread hopes that the pace of the
economy has moderated enough to contain inflationary pressures
such as rising production costs.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
jumped from late Monday's 6.54 percent to 6.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
Banks and other financial issues, which enjoy a smaller profit
margin on the loans they make when interest rates rise, were among
the day's weakest groups.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's biggest decliners included several of the year's
leaders, including General Electric and IBM.  
</P>
</TEXT>
