<HEADLINE> Man Shot Outside Home of Alleged Former Nazi in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A man was shot and wounded
by police outside home of an alleged former Nazi, whose U.S.
citizenship was sought by the Justice Department to be revoked.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear if the elderly man was Michael
Kolnhofer, 79, of Kansas City, Kansas, an immigrant suspected of
being a former concentration camp guard and member of the
Waffen-SS during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the Justice Department's Office of Special
Investigations (OSI) in Washington filed court papers seeking to
strip him of his U.S. citizenship that often lead to deportation.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said at the home listed by federal
officials as Kolnhofer's address, a man came out and waved a black
handgun at reporters and said, "Are you going to go away? Are you
going to go away?"
</P>
<P>
The man cocked the gun and pointed it at several reporters, who
scrambled for cover, it said.
</P>
<P>
When police were called to the scene, the man fired shots and
police returned fire.
</P>
<P>
Citing captured wartime Nazi records, the Justice Department
said Kolnhofer in January 1943 became a member of the SS Death's
Head Guard Battalion at Sachsenhausen, near Berlin, where he served
as a guard until January 1944.
</P>
<P>
SS personnel records show Kolnhofer was transferred in January
1944 to Buchenwald concentration camp near Weimar, Germany.
</P>
<P>
"The defendant concealed his Nazi concentration camp guard
service from U.S. immigration officials when he immigrated to this
country from Germany in 1952, and he never would have received a
U.S. visa had he disclosed the truth," the OSI said in a statement
today.
</P>
<P>
To date, 57 former Nazis have been revoked of U.S. citizenship
and 48 have been removed from the United States since OSI began
operation in 1979, the U.S. attorney's office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
