<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy indicated
surprising signs of strength today as reports showed consumer
confidence at a seven-year high and new home sales up
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a business research group based in New
York, said its Consumer Confidence Index for December rose
markedly by 4.3 points from November to 113.8, its highest level
since November 1989, when it reached 115.1.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the Commerce Department reported new home sales
unexpectedly rose 14.2 percent in November, the steepest advance
in 3 years and more.
</P>
<P>
The figures were well above economists' estimates.
</P>
<P>
Both reports disappointed financial markets, which have been
hoping for continued signs of moderate economic growth and low
inflation that have spurred big gains throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
The yield on the Treasury's main 30-year bond rose 0.09
percentage point to 6.63 percent. Blue-chip stock prices plunged,
with the Dow Jones industrial average falling 101.10 points to
6,448.27, the biggest since a 161.05-point drop July 15.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Confidence Index, calculated from a 1985 base of
100, is derived from responses to questions sent to 5,000
households nationwide, polling them on matters ranging from job
availability to home-buying plans.
</P>
<P>
A separate measure of sentiment about current business
conditions rose to a seven-year high of 136.4 in December, up
three points from November.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 percent of surveyed families described current
business conditions as good in December and only 6 percent of
consumers expected conditions to deteriorate, the lowest figure in
eight years.
</P>
<P>
About 14 percent said jobs were difficult to find this month,
down from 17 percent in November.  
</P>
</TEXT>
