<HEADLINE> Murders Rate Drops in Major U.S. Cities in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The rate of murders in most
of U.S. cities has dropped in 1996 due to the reenforcement of
police and tougher punishment to criminals, the Police Executive
Research Forum said today.
</P>
<P>
Boston and New York dropped to their lowest levels since the
1960s. As of Tuesday morning, Boston had 58 murders, fewer than
any 12-month period since 1966.
</P>
<P>
In New York, murders have dropped more than 50 percent since
1990, from 2,245 to fewer than 1,000 in 1996, the lowest number
since 1968. Phoenix kept the number of homicides to 205 in 1996
from 244 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
As of December 14, Los Angeles reported 688 homicides, 141 less
than the same period last year, or an 11.1 percent drop. And
Dallas reported 219 homicide toll in 1996, half its homicide toll
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The drop of murders rate coincideds with the increase of police
forces in the cities. Over the past two years, Boston has added
300 officers and New York put 7,000 more police officers in the
street. Phoenix has increased the 10 percent of its law
enforcement force since last year.
</P>
<P>
The drops were also attributed to longer, mandatory sentences
for violent criminals and a decline in the number of men in their
late teens and early 20s.
</P>
<P>
However, some big cities, including Atlanta, Las Vegas, Miami
and Washington, reported higher numbers of homicides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Says Bosnia Has No Military, Intelligence Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA) said today Bosnia has broken military and
intelligence ties with Iran and no organized foreign forces remain
on its soil, a condition for the U.S. to go ahead with a plan to
train and equip troops of the Balkan country early next year.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic was credited with taking an
aggressive approach in breaking with Iran. "He recognizes his
relationship with us is more important than anything he could have
with Iran," said John Dinger, a State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The largely Muslim government in Bosnia-Herzegovina made
liberal use of weapons from Iran and other Muslim countries to
fight Serbs in their conflicts before U.S.-led negotiations that
produced peace accords a year ago.
</P>
<P>
After the Dayton peace accords were signed, scores of Iranian
and other foreign fighters remained behind. The western nations
showed their concern about it and delayed delivery of weapons to
Bosnian forces under a "train-and-equip" program designed to put
them on a relatively equal footing with Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
American intelligence has concluded Bosnia has severed its
military and intelligence links with Iran, Central Intelligence
Agency spokesman David Christian said Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
