<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Foreign Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
economic center, is expected to export 13 billion worth of
commodities in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite the nation's strained environment for foreign trade
last year, Shanghai still achieved a much better result than
expected, said Jiang Yiren, Shanghai's deputy mayor in charge of
foreign trade affairs.
</P>
<P>
The export and import values for the first 11 months of 1996
have grown 13.25 percent and 32.6 percent over the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Shanghai's contractual foreign investment is expected
to top the record of 10.5 billion US dollars set in 1995. The city
has brought in 10 billion US dollars worth of contractual foreign
investment in the first eleven months, as a result of 1,966 new
projects approved during the period.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the projects, involving 400 million US
dollars, are well underway.  
</P>
