<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Achieves Record High Revenue in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, produced 55.55 billion yuan in revenue in 1996,
an increase of 25.6 percent over the previous year, or the record
high.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Youdao, director of Shanghai Municipal Finance Bureau
announced today that Shanghai's revenue growth has surpassed the
increase rate of the city's GDP for three years successively as
the municipal government has adopted a series of measures to
promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
The policy of invigorating large state-owned enterprises and
setting smaller ones free as well as measures to enhance
technological renovation, re-organization and the development of
high-tech industries have also helped achieve the new increase, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The largest part of revenue increase, Zhou said, comes from the
second industry, followed by service sector. Tax income from
private and individual enterprises came up to 2.2 billion yuan, up
by 28 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
