<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Develops Oceanic Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province, boasting a 487-kilometer coastline, has made marked
achievements in developing oceanic industries since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
Within the province's sea area are more than 200 kinds of
oceanic living beings. The varieties of fish alone stand at
110. The seawater also contains more than 80 kinds of chemical
elements. And there are rich oil and gas resources in the
continental shelf area, with their reserves listed at 2.3 billion
tons and 34 billion square meters. The province also boasts
favorable conditions for port-building along its coastline.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao Port has become one of the world's largest energy
resources export ports, with its annual handling capacity of coal
and crude oil reaching nearly 100 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Two berths with a capacity of 5,000 tons at the Jing-Tang port
have gone into operation, and two berths at Huanghua port, each
with a capacity of 3,000 tons, also opened to navigation. A group
of wharves with capacities ranging from 10,000 tons to 100,000
tons are under construction.
</P>
<P>
The province has established 96 saltworks, covering a total
area of 382,000 hectares. Its output of crude salt accounts for
one-fifth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The province's offshore oil production has reached five million
tons annually. A group of offshore oil wells are also expected to
go into operation soon.
</P>
<P>
Hebei Province has developed a group of tourism spots along its
coastline which received 40 million tourists annually, and bring
in more than 400 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
