<HEADLINE> Record Number of Passengers Travel Through Rome Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The International Leonardo Da
Vinci Airport registered a record for the year ending today of
more than 23 million passengers in transit, 9.2 percent up over
the figure of 21,091,380 passengers handled in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The total number of passengers flying into or out from the two
airports in the Italian capital, Leonardo Da Vinci and the
Ciampino military and civilian airport, amounted to nearly 24
million, more than 2 million up compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of flights logged also rose by 13.7 percent to
238,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase was constant throughout the year and was boosted
in the last week of December when, over the weekend of December 28
and 29, more than 124,000 passengers moved through Leonardo Da
Vinci, 13 percent up over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday and Sunday, the big Rome airport handled 62,800 and
55,600 passengers respectively. On Monday, the number hit 61,400,
a gain of 7,300 compared to the same day last year.
</P>
<P>
On Christmas Day, the airport received 28,400 passengers, 25
percent more than last Christmas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
