<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Grain Production Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Xinjiang, a major bread basket in
northwest China, produced over eight million tons of grain in
1996, up by 700,000 tons over that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The new record was broken after the Uygur autonomous region
achieved an annual grain increase of 200,000 to 300,000 tons each
year in the past few years and suffered from a major natural
disaster in 1996, said Zhang Hen, vice chairman of the autonomous
region.
</P>
<P>
Zhang attributed the new bumper harvest to the increase in sown
areas, larger investment and greater application of new
agro-technologies.
</P>
<P>
The construction of water-saving and grain production projects
as well as China's latest increase in grain purchasing prices in
1996 have encouraged local farmers in grain production, prompting
them to buy more chemical fertilizer, farm machines and new
agro-technologies, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Rebels Release Two More Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian rebels occupying the
residence of the Japanese ambassador here released two more
hostages today, leaving 81 hostages in the compound.
</P>
<P>
The two men were identified as Honduran Ambassador Jose Eduardo
Martel Mejia and Argentine Consul General Juan Antonio Ibanez.
</P>
<P>
They, accompanied by Red Cross officials, walked out the
Japanese ambassador's residence just hours before New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
The release of the Honduran ambassador came shortly before
Honduran Foreign Minister Delmer Urbizo Panting arrived here at
18:30 local time.
</P>
<P>
The rebels allowed reporters and photographers to enter the
residence of Japanese Ambassador Morihisa Aoki for the first time
today since a group of some 20 rebels of the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) occupied the compound on December 17.
</P>
<P>
Four hostages, including Peruvian Foreign Minister Francisco
Tudela, Congressman Gilberto Siura and Ambassador Morihisa Aoki,
were allowed to meet the press.
</P>
<P>
Tudela said that he was going through difficult times in the
past few days and he was reading and thinking about his country.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader, Nestor Cerpa Cartolini, read a message to
reporters, insisting that some 400 imprisoned MRTA members be set
free from jails to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
His tough public line contradicted earlier hints that the
rebels might soften their demands.
</P>
<P>
Cerpa Cartolini proposed that the crisis be solved with no
"losers or winners."
</P>
<P>
The local radio station "Programa" reported that President
Alberto Fujimori and Domingo Palermo, the government delegate for
the hostage crisis, met later in the day to discuss the MRTA
message.
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross Committee in a bulletin emphasized
its intention to contribute to the establishment of direct
contacts between the government mediator and the MRTA commando.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
