<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The period between September 1 and December 15
recorded a shipment of 13.6 million boxes of fruit and vegetables
for export, said the Association of Chilean Exporters.
</P>
<P>
The fruit and vegetable went to foreign markets of Latin
American countries, North America and Europe, it said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of this sector totalled 2.095 billion U.S. dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Private and state investments in Uruguay's
tourist sector reached 387 million U.S. dollars this year, an
increase of 88.3 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Bank deposits in Argentina increased by 28.3
percent this year, from 41.741 billion dollars on January 1 to
53.564 billion dollars on December 17.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will have to pay 830 million U.S. dollars to
Paris Club creditors between December 30 and January 6, of which
479.2 million dollars consists of amortizations and the remaining
350.8 million dollars as interest payments.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The privatizations carried out in Peru in 1996
generated revenues of more than 2.5 billion U.S. dollars for the
public treasury, apart from another 2.7 billion dollars in
investment pledges.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Gonzalez Izquierdo, chairman of Peru's Privatization
Commission, announced that another 14 companies will be sold off
to the private sector in 1997 and the state will receive another
1.6 billion dollars from those sales.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- A total of 989,000 hectares of land has been
earmarked in Argentina for cotton planting during the 1996-97
growing season, a 2.1 percent decrease over the previous growing
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
