<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Investing in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guangzhou, January 1 (Xinhua ) -- A new trend in China's
Guangdong Province is for large and medium-sized industries to
invest in farming, and to run farms as large-scale businesses, a
move that has intensified agricultural development, according to
some local experts.
</P>
<P>
The companies have invested in growing fruit, forestry, and
raising fish, and are building farm products-processing factories
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of last year, over 50 local companies drew
up plans to invest several billion yuan in farming, and so far,
over one billion yuan has been put into the area, according to
provincial statistics.
</P>
<P>
With the extra funds, the companies have introduced new
technology and management to the agricultural sector, bringing a
large number of farmers to intensively-managed, modernized
agricultural production, and allowing them to reduce their risk.
</P>
<P>
Most of the companies have shown a profit and have helped
farmers have a better life, according to the experts, who say that
industrialized production and better management could make
agriculture one of the most profitable sectors.
</P>
<P>
Some of the companies have expanded their investment to other
provinces in northeast and northwest China, which are the
country's major grain and cotton producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
