<HEADLINE> New Year Messages of Eastern, Central European Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state of some of the
eastern and central European countries assured their people of a
better future in their new year messages on the eve of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha said that the passing 1996 is a
year of peace, democracy, liberty and happiness for his country.
</P>
<P>
In a new year message delivered today in the capital of Tirana,
Berisha said that Albania enjoyed the fastest economic growth rate
in Europe in 1996 and the country has played an important role in
maintaining peace and stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide televised new year address, Romanian President
Emil Constantinescu said his country will try to build a "healthy
economy" in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
He said 1997 will also be a key year for Romania to join the
European Union and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian President Zheliu Zhelev called 1996 the most
difficult year for his country since 1989. But he said he believes
that the Bulgarian people will find a correct path for the country
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian President Goncz Arpad, in his new year message,
expressed his confidence in the country's bright future. He said
the nation's economy, now in the last phase of privatization, has
started to rebound, Goncz said.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Macedonian capital of Skoplje said President Kiro
Gligorov stressed that the country will accelerate its process to
merge its economy into the European and world markets.
</P>
<P>
Gligorov said that Macedonia will continue its market reform
and draw more foreign investment in the coming year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
