<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Army Chief Calls for Discipline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Army Commander Rohan
de S. Daluwatte, in a New Year message to all ranks, civilian
staff and their families today, stressed the need for discipline
to usher in the much- needed peace for the country in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his message, he said that 1996 was the most decisive year in
the history of the country. Both the Jaffna Peninsula and
Kilinochchi Town were liberated from the hands of the separatist
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
</P>
<P>
The Army is then entrusted with the task of preparing the
groundwork for establishing civil administration in these areas
and it is able to fulfill that responsibility, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He asked his troops not to be discouraged by reversals, but to
work hard to avoid them in the future.
</P>
<P>
The commander admitted that a few acts of indiscipline occurred
in the past year and they "brought dishonor to the armed forces
and the nation in general."
</P>
<P>
"Everyone of us should resolve to work as disciplined soldiers
without being enslaved by emotional feelings. As soldiers, our
prime duty is to protect all peace-loving sections of the
community and work in harmony with them," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
