<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Growth in Brazil to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The annual population
growth rate in Brazil will decrease from 1.4 percent to 1.15
percent by the year 2000, said the Brazilian Institute of
Geography and Statistics (IBGE).
</P>
<P>
The IBGE projected in its latest study that Brazil will have a
population of 165.7 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The study says that the Brazilian population, estimated at 158
million in 1996, will stabilize at 230 million between 2030 and
2040.
</P>
<P>
The average birth rate for Brazilian women will drop from the
present 2.4 children per female to 1.8 children, leading to a
slow-down in population growth.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1991 census, the annual national rate of
population growth was 1.9 percent since 1980.
</P>
<P>
Between 1965 and 1970, Brazilian women had an average of 6
children. After 25 years the rate dropped to 3.5 children per
female, according to the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
