<HEADLINE> Dhaka Ushers In New Year With Firecrackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- People set off firecrackers and
blew the horns of their cars in the Bangladeshi capital to usher
in the new year as the clock struck 12 Tuesday night marking the
arrival of the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Jubilant boys and girls came out of their houses dancing and
singing to welcome the new year while huge crowds were seen
gathering on streets all over the city.
</P>
<P>
Youths were also spotted on reckless driving as part of the new
year merry making.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, uniformed policemen and special teams of the
detective branch kept a sharp eye on the late-night revelers. But
no untoward incident was reported immediately, officials concerned
said.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the city had been in a festive atmosphere throughout
the day Tuesday as huge gatherings were seen at card shops in
different markets as teenage boys and girls bought greeting cards
to wish their beloved ones happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
The city also ran short of flowers as people bought them up as
new year gifts although florists doubled or tripled their prices.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the nation, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
expressed her good wishes to the people and hoped the new year
will bring peace and prosperity to the nation.
</P>
<P>
She called upon the people, irrespective of political ideology
and belief, to join hands in carrying the nation forward and
ensuring a prosperous future for the posterity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
