<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Lifts Ban on Russian-Made Helicopters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A ban on passenger services by
Russian-made Mi-17 helicopters in Nepal was lifted only hours
after it came into effect, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The government has granted permits to operators of the
Russian-made helicopters allowing them to continue passenger
operations soon after the ban was imposed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Civil Aviation had earlier announced that the
existing 12 Mi-17s in the country, belonging to four private
airlines, would be forbidden to carry out passenger operations
starting December 30 because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
Helicopter operators complained that such a ban would have an
adverse impact on the country's tourism industry and obstruct
disaster relief operations in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
They said the Russian-made helicopters, which began their
commercial services in Nepal in 1993 and account for about 46
percent of Nepal's domestic air seat capacity, have made a
significant contribution to the transportation of goods and
passengers to remote hilly areas, especially some favorite tourist
destinations.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the Department of Civil Aviation would set up
a technical committee, comprising experts from the government and
private airlines, to study the passenger-carrying capabilities of
the Mi-17 helicopters.
</P>
<P>
A final ruling on these helicopters is to be made on the basis
of the technical committee's report, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Introduce New Population Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- India is expected to introduce
a new national population policy soon in a bid to curb population
explosion in the country, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft of the new national population policy,
which is on the anvil, all new entrants to the government who are
married before the legal age will be debarred from recruitment.
</P>
<P>
Steps will also be taken to see that the two-child norm is
adopted by government employees both at the national and state
levels. Promotion policies will also be formulated to encourage
the two-child norm in an effort to control growth in the country's
population, which is expected to exceed 1 billion by the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
The new policy will make it mandatory for employers of the
organized sector to provide for group health insurance as
incentive. Besides, legislation will be enacted to debar from
elective offices those people who do not adopt the small family
norm.
</P>
<P>
The draft population policy also stresses the need for men to
be equal partners in family planning.
</P>
<P>
It warns that if the population policy goes wrong, "nothing
else will have a chance to go right."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Bangladesh Start Sharing Ganges Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- India and Bangladesh today
formally started sharing the common Ganges water after India
opened 75 sluice-gates of its Farakka barrage at 06:30 a.m. local
time (0030 GMT) in implementation of an agreement between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
India and Bangladesh signed a 30-year water-sharing treaty on
December 12, 1996, to resolve their long-standing dispute over the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh had accused India of withdrawing the Ganges water at
the upper stream, thus greatly reducing the water flowing into
Bangladesh during the dry season beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, the release of the Ganges water through
the Farakka will enable Bangladesh to irrigate vast tracts of
land, increase underground water level, check desertification and
ease salinity in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
To monitor the flow of water, Indian experts have been staying
at the Farakka point since December 25 while Bangladeshi water
experts are expected to arrive there at noon today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
