<HEADLINE> India to Revive Capital Market Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
expected to announce a series of measures in the next two weeks
for reviving the capital market, reducing capital expenditure,
further deregulating the economy and lifting the credit squeeze,
business sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
This was a promise made by Prime Minister Deve Gowda to
industrialists at a five-hour meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, industrialists demanded immediate steps for the
revival of the depressed capital market, faster clearances at the
state government level, reduction of government equity to below 50
percent in public-sector units, lower interest rates, easy
availability of the rupee in two years and opening of the
insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
The industrialists came out of the marathon meeting "with a
strong sense of satisfaction that the government would be taking
some firm decisions very soon," the same sources said.  
</P>
