<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Rights in Nepal in "Depressing" State: NGO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A non-governmental
organization (NGO) in Nepal described the state of child rights in
the country as "depressing" in its annual report released here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Child Workers in Nepal (CWIN) Concerned Center said that
despite positive developments, child rights violations are still
common in Nepal in forms like child labor, child marriage and
trafficking of children for forced prostitution.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that 1 million Nepali children are engaged
in child labor, with about 60 percent of them working in high-risk
conditions, such as the sex trade, mines, stone quarries and the
carpet industry.
</P>
<P>
It also said that every year some 4,000 to 5,000 Nepali
children, mostly girls, are trafficked into neighboring India for
prostitution or bonded labor.
</P>
<P>
Despite the prohibition of child marriage by a law enacted more
than 30 years ago, such marriages still prevail in rural and poor
urban areas in the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The CWIN report also noted some favorite developments in
protecting child rights in Nepal, such as the government's
commitment to the implementation of the U.N. Convention on Child
Rights, a national plan of action for protecting child rights and
an increasing social awareness on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The NGO report urged the government to provide free and
compulsory education for children in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
