<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Vows to Resist Ruling Party's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Nationalist Party
(BNP), the country's main opposition, has warned the government
that the party will soon build resistance instead of just
protesting against the ruling party's "conspiracy" to run
parliament without opposition.
</P>
<P>
The BNP, the second largest party in the parliament next to the
ruling Awami League (AL), walked out of the house on November 10
to press for its 10-point demand including a "neutral role" of the
speaker and the state-run Bangladesh TV as well as halting
"repression" on BNP workers.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the BNP's peasant front -- the Jatiyatabadi
Krishak Dal -- last night, BNP Secretary General Abdul Mannan
Bhuiyan said that the government hatched a conspiracy so that the
opposition cannot return to parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party "did not hold any formal or informal
discussion with us to resolve the crisis through meeting our
demands," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to go back to the parliament and we have
already placed our demands in this regard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local English newspaper the Daily Star today
reported that both the ruling AL and the opposition BNP have
softened their stance, signaling a solution to the stalemate in
the house.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the daily last night, leaders of both sides
expressed their hope to resolve the main issues that created the
stalemate and showed eagerness to ensure that the parliament sits
with members of both benches when its first session of the new
year begins on January 15, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
