<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Province Attracting More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 1 (Xinhua)-- China's most populous province,
Sichuan, is encouraging more foreign companies to invest in its
banking, foreign trade, retail, and tourism sectors.
</P>
<P>
Preferential tax policies will be provided for foreign
cooperation in developing wasteland, improving low-yield farmland,
and other large-scale agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
Overseas business people can build storage facilities,
transport farm produce, and build communications and energy
projects.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan approved 294 overseas-funded enterprises, involving 516
million US dollars, in the first 11 months of 1996, bringing the
province's use of overseas capital up to 12 billion US dollars,
putting it first in western China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Sichuan had 6,268 overseas-funded
enterprises, and more than 30 transnational corporations have
invested in the province.
</P>
<P>
To open wider to the outside world, Sichuan will focus on
developing the Chengdu-Chongqing Expressway area and the Yangtze
River, and several high-tech industrial zones as well as a special
investment zone for Taiwanese businessmen, according to Deputy
Governor Li Dachang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
