<HEADLINE> New Year's Flag-Raising Ceremony In Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 people from
across China braved the windy biting cold and frozen snow of
Tiananmen Square early this morning for the first flag-raising
ceremony of the new year, many having come to the square hours
ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
The nation's flag was hoisted to the strains of the national
anthem at 7:36 A.M.
</P>
<P>
"This is a meaningful way to greet the new year. We'll work
harder to make things better in this year of great importance,"
said Beijing's standing mayor Jia Qinglin.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 Hong Kong students studying at the Beijing Youth
Political College, told Xinhua that they are looking forward to
the day when Hong Kong returns to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The flag used today was also special -- it is the first flag
carried into outer space by a Chinese satellite, which circled the
earth for 15 days, returning on November 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Today I felt very excited and proud because this is the first
time our flag has been sent into space by our own retrievable
satellite," said Lin Huarong, a satellite engineer from the China
Aerospace Corporation.
</P>
<P>
China has been in the forefront, along with the United States
and Russia in the technology to develop retrievable satellites,
according to Lin.
</P>
<P>
"I've seen flag-raising ceremonies a number of times, but this
one is special because it is symbolic of our great achievements in
space technology," said Niu Zhuo, a Beijing high school student.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, the flag was given to the Museum of Chinese
History for display. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
