<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Year's Celebrations Across China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- People across China celebrated
the first day of the new year with joyful gatherings, looking for
the new year to be more promising and hopeful.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital was blanketed with a moderate snow fall on
Tuesday. Snow is always regarded by the Chinese as an auspicious
sign for a coming new year.
</P>
<P>
At 7:36 this morning, more than 50,000 people throughout China
came to Tian'anmen Square to watch the national flag-raising
ceremony, braving a biting wind.
</P>
<P>
The flag that was raised was noteworthy for having been in
outer space for 15 days in a Chinese satellite that returned on
November 4.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, many people walked across the square to an
electronic board that marks the the countdown to the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland. Some people took photos as a momento.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, municipal
officials joined ordinary citizens to say happy new year greetings
to each other.
</P>
<P>
One official said in his speech that 1997 will be extremely
important in Chinese history, because Hong Kong will return to the
motherland and the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party
of China will be held.
</P>
<P>
Municipal officials and ordinary folk in Tianjin in northern
China held a happy get-together on December 31 to welcome the new
year. More than 100 performances have been or will be staged in
the city's urban and suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
In southern China, where the weather is warmer, the new year
was met with blossoms, as streets and parks in Guangzhou, the
provincial capital of Guangdong, were dotted with fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, more than 40 trucks ornamented with flowers,
drove about the city's streets, catching residents' attention and
announcing the beginning of '97 China Tourism there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
