<HEADLINE> New Year's Celebrations Across China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kunming, in the southwest, basked in bright sunlight as
residents, both old and young, flocked to a park in the center of
the city to watch gulls, whose numbers have been increasing in
recent years, thanks to environmental improvements and the locals'
friendliness.
</P>
<P>
In Fuzhou, Nanchang, and Changsha, groups of people could be
seen in streets and parks festooned with flowers, ribbons,
balloons and lanterns.
</P>
<P>
In northeast China, the coldness of winter did not keep people
from welcoming the new year, even though many cities lay covered
with snow.
</P>
<P>
Local culture departments have been busy organizing
performances. An ice and snow art exhibition was held in Changchun
City, giving people a taste of some well-known buildings in
different styles from around the world.
</P>
<P>
Entertainments in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region also drew local people from across the grasslands, which
are blanketed with snow.
</P>
<P>
People in many other places began the new year by engaging in
healthful activities. Residents in Xi'ning participated in the
24th around-the-city race on January 1.
</P>
<P>
People in Nanjing, Chengdu, Yinchuan, Hefei, and Guiyang cities
also take part in long-distance runs to welcome the new year.
</P>
<P>
Other places started the new year in various ways, such as
tourism promotions, public gatherings, and volunteer work.
