<HEADLINE> Army, Shanghai Win in Basketball First Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Army Rockets drubbed Guangdong
Tigers 108-82 in a Chinese men's basketball first division match
in Xi'an, northwest Shaanxi Province on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In other actions on New Year's Day, Shanghai Oriental downed
Beijing Ducks 91-72 in Beijing while Shandong Flaming Bulls beat
Jiangsu Nangang 93-78 in Jinan, Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Rockets, which suffered its only loss this season to Liaoning
Hunters last month, led the first half 57-47 and took full
advantage of Tigers' weak stamina in the second half.
</P>
<P>
Army's Liu Yudong scored 23 points and Liu Qiang added 22 as
another three of their teammates had double digit scores.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's Zhang Yongjun led all players with 32 points, while
Li Chunjiang had 16 and Ouyang Guijing had 11.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, the win of Shanghai Oriental over the host let
Shanghai maintain its joint socond place with Liaoning Hunters
with a 9-2 record.
</P>
<P>
Lithuanian Saulius Stombergas scored a game-high 31 points and
nine rebounds for the Oriental, which took a 49-43 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's 18-6 run 9:30 into the second half extended the
score to 67-49, also confirming its winning situation.
</P>
<P>
Bateer, 2.10-meter center, contributed 27 points and 14
rebounds for Beijing, held to only 29 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
"This was one of the worst games we played this season," said
Yuan Chao, head coach of the Ducks, which were a 4-7 record. "We
were bad defensevily and offensevily, espcially in the second
half."
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, a new team this season with two Lithunians and four
non-Shanghai native players, just lost first two games this season
to Army Rockets and Guangdong Tigers apiece.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy for the results," Shanghai coach Li Qiuping
said. "Next step we will try to get a best place in the league."
</P>
<P>
In Jinan, Gong Xiaobin scored 29 points and Yang Wenhai
contributed 19 for Shandong as the Flaming Bulls gored Jiangsu
Nangang at home.
</P>
<P>
American John Spencer led Nangang with 22 points and teammate
Hu Weidong added 17.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu coach Xia Hongfa said, "Our strength under the basket
is weak. We had problems in morale and solidarity in the
second. It is we who beat ourselves today."
</P>
<P>
Shandong coach Ye Peng said, "We fought hard today. I am
satisfied."
</P>
<P>
The remaining three matches of the 11th round will played on
Sunday, with Liaoning Hunters facing Sichuan Pandas, Zhejiang
Squirrels meeting Lianhang Eagles and Jinan Pegasus facing
Shenyang Lions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
