<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Begins 'Door-to-door' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian exporters as of today
can deliver their goods directly to the Israelis without
unloading them to be checked near the borders.
</P>
<P>
The "door-to-door" arranmgement, which took effect today, was
signed last November by Jordan and Israel to replace a
"back-to-back" system under which all Jordanian goods entering
Israel had to be offloaded on the Jordan's side of the border
crossings and reloaded after Israeli inspections onto Israeli
vehicles on the other side.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Transport Nasser Lawzi has said that
the "door-to-door" arrangement allows the direct transport of
goods across the Jordan Valley and the Wadi Arab crossings all
week days except Fridays and Saturdays, Jordan Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangement, large vehicles will be issued
extendible three-day entry permission at the crossing points. If
the driver of the vehicle could not return to his country on the
same day, he should call the nearest police station to register
his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
The driver should also hold a valid license, passport and
entry visa.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement was worked out after persistent efforts by
the Jordanian government following complaints by exporters that
the "back-to-back" arrangement caused undue delays and
expenses. In many cases, goods were damaged or became rotten in
the process.
</P>
<P>
The "door-to-door" arrangement is limited to Jordanian exports
to Israel now and will be applied to the flow of goods between
Jordan and the Palestinian territories at a later stage, Jordan
Times said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Israel has agreed to allow Jordanian trucks
carrying cement to the Palestinian territories to be covered
under the new arrangement. Oil shipments are also permitted, but
the actual flow of such items is expected later.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel in 1994 signed a peace agreement in which a
transport accord was also included. But Israel did not fully
implement the agreement. In the past two years, it had always
been criticized by Jordan for delaying the Jordanian exports to
Israel on purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
