<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese Province's '97 China Tourism Year Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Jinan, the capital of east China's
Shandong province, received its first groups of tourists from
Germany this morning, marking its beginning of the '97 China
Tourism Year.
</P>
<P>
Li Chunting, the provincial governor, greeted visitors from
China and from overseas, and said he hopes more people will visit
the hometown of Confucius, who is considered ancient China's
greatest philosopher and educator.
</P>
<P>
The '97 China Tourism Year (Shandong) hopes to draw more people
to the Shandong tourism fair, a tourism festival, and Mount Tai,
one of the country's five famous mountains, located in Tai'an city.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province, which had seen rapid growth in its tourism
in the past few years, became one of the top 10 provinces in 1995
in term of the number of tourists and income from the sector.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 tourists visited Jinan, which is renowned as "the
city of springs", last year, bringing it an income of 24 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The China National Tourism Administration estimates that
approximately 50 million tourists from overseas are expected to
tour China in 1997, generating some 10 billion US dollars in
tourism income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
