<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 43 PKK Rebels Killed in Turkey's Cross-Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- forty-three rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in the
cross-border operations by the Turkish security forces in
northern Iraq in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today that
Turkish F-4 fighters taking off from the air base in Diyarbakir,
southeastern Turkey, had bombarded three PKK camps in Sinath
region, 10 kilometers deep into northern Iraq early this morning
in the cross-border operations which started Monday night.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 Turkish troops and village guards attacked the PKK
militants who tried to flee from Sindi throat in northern Iraq
following the bombardment of the Cobra helicopters, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
It also said that two soldiers of the Turkish security forces
died in the clashes with the PKK guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have entered into northern Iraq for several
times in attempts to destroy the military bases from where the
PKK launch cross-border attacks against Turkish targets.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government, which have been deprived of the control over
northern Kurdish area by the allied forces, have made protests
against the Turkish operations before, accusing Turkey of
violation of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces have killed 13,255 PKK rebels,
wounded 244 and captured about 2,000 since August 1984 when the
PKK started guerrilla war in southeastern Turkey, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,900 soldiers of the security forces have been also
killed in clashes with the militant group.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the security forces wiped out 2,782 PKK rebels,
injured 36 and captured about 320 in the military operations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
More than 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in the conflicts in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
