<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Construction In East Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- By intensifying the construction
of its infrastructure construction, east China's coastal province
of Fujian has seen its economic growth rate in 1996 go up, a
provincial government official said.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, Fujian's GDP reached 260 billion yuan (about
31 billion US dollars), and imports and exports totalled 16
billion US dollars, up 15 percent and 9.3 percent respectively,
according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
The economic achievements are partly attributed to heavy
investment in infrastructure over the past few years, the official
explained, saying that, in 1996 alone, the province invested
over 20 billion yuan in highway, port, and airport construction.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Fujian has built a total of 45,000 km. of
highways, and is building three new railways and 22 new ports to
help the development of transportation.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the modern Changle International Airport, at a
total cost of 2.47 billion yuan, is close to completion, while
expansion of an international airport in Xiamen was completed just
a few days ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
