<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 600,000 Yuan Worth Of Salt Used On Beijing's First Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital got a
dusting of snow on the last day of 1996 and was white for New
Year's Day, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The snow did ease the winter driness to some extent and clean
the air, but it cost the city's environmental control department
600,000 yuan (some 72,000 U.S. dollars) to help dissolve it in
order to avoid traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 sanitation workers dispatched by the municipal
environmental department sprayed salt water on 91 flyovers and 53
arterial roads in the city. Some 4,100 tons of salt water made
from 800 tons of salt was sprayed on the city's roads from 7:30
Tuesday evening to 5:00 A.M. today.
</P>
<P>
Beijing was clear and freezing cold today with a low of minus
seven centigrade, and there was still some snow and ice left on
the trunk lines, such as Chang'an Avenue and the Second and Third
ring roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
