<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls on Arafat, Netanyahu To Speed Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Karim Kabariti Tuesday made telephone calls to Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, urging them to speed up action for final status talks,
the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti made the calls in response to the fact that the two
sides signed an initial accord on Israeli handover of the West
Bank city of Hebron to the Palestinians after a whole day's
negotiation, the local daily Jordan Times reported.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides did not succeed in reaching a final
agreement on Hebron which was expected to be signed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hebron is the last West Bank city still under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
Under the Palestinian-Israeli peace accord, the Palestinians
will experience a five-year period of self-rule as transition to
a permanent settlement, beginning in April 1994. By April 1997,
final status negotiations shall begin on Jerusalem, settlements,
refugees, borders and security.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti pressed Arafat and Netanyahu to implement provisions
of interim agreements, so that the final status talks could begin
in a positive spirit that would contribute to enhancing prospects
for achieving a just, comprehensive and durable peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has recently been criticizing Israel for its hardline
policy and is eager to see the Hebron agreement to be finalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
