<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Premier On Agriculture Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- On an inspection tour of
Xinsheng Village in the Chaoyang District of Beijing, Vice Premier
Jiang Chunyun urged six million workers who are involved in a
national agricultural survey to make certain data are accurate,
correct and reliable.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Beijing's acting mayor, Jia Qinglin, the vice
premier said the survey, which started today, is the first ever in
China, and will help the government improve agriculture sector
controls.
</P>
<P>
More than six million workers will visit some 230 million rural
households in approximately 800,000 villages and more than 20
million rural enterprises for the survey.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the quality of registration work should be high
so that results represent the real conditions in China's
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Local governments should not place financial burdens on farmers
in the name of the survey, he said, calling for coordination
between local governments and farmers in order to ensure success in
the survey, which will clarify the amount of farmland, the size
and quality of the rural labor force, and the number of people who
have migrated to cities to look for work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
