<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1500 GMT, January 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today
sharply condemned the shooting incident carried out by an Israeli
soldier in downtown Hebron earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest Israel Radio report, which could not be
confirmed by either the Israeli Government Press Office or the
Army's spokesman, six Palestinians were wounded, and one of them
seriously, during the shooting attack.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian's Jerusalem Media and Communications
Center, contacted by phone, said that plus the six wounded by
gunshots five other Palestinian shoppers were beaten and injured
by Israeli soldiers shortly after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Radio report said that Noam Friedman, 19, an
Orthodox resident of Ma'aleh Adumim, who is in his three-year
mandatory military service, but not posted in Hebron, carried out
the attack by himself.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
attacked a Turk-Telekom radio-link station in southeastern Turkey
on the new year eve.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News said today that no casualties were
reported in the attack in Ergani district of Diyarbakir.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted security officials as saying that operations
were underway in the region to capture the PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces have killed 13,255 PKK militants,
wounded 244 and captured about 2,000 in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- At least five Tamil rebels were killed today when
they confronted government troops in Eastern province of Sri
Lanka, according to a military news release.
</P>
<P>
The release said that government troops confronted a group of
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) this morning
 at Thampalancholai southwest of Batticaloa town.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a 13-year war against the
Sri Lankan government in a bid for a separate state. More than
55,000 people have been reportedly killed during the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
