<HEADLINE> Sino-German Chemical Joint Venture Goes into Operation In South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A large Sino-German joint
chemical production venture has gone into operation today in the
capital city of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Huali Sachtleben Chemicals Co. Ltd., with a total
investment of 173 million yuan (20.8 million US dollars), was set
up by the Guangzhou Huali Pitment Chemical Industry Company and
Germany's Sachtleben Company.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou company, a four-decade-old state-owned business,
which is part of the Guangzhou Chemical Industry Group,
contributed 60 percent of the new venture's funding. Its annual
business volume is worth 230 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The German, which dates back 180 years, has a considerable
economic and technological edge in the business.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is expected to turn out some 50,000 tons of
lithopone annually, 60 percent of which will be exported.  
</P>
