<HEADLINE> Drug Trafficking Rampant in Western Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A drug trafficking syndicate is
active in Natore region in western Bangladesh, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star, an English daily in the country, has
investigated the trafficking activities in the region recently.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation, the drug traffickers have
changed their strategy and are now using river routes for
marketing Indian-made phensidyl, a kind of drug, to different
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The phensidyl traders use boats that ply from Taherpur and
Shadhanpur in the region, the daily said, adding that about 100 to
150 boats leave the two areas for Dhaka twice a week and each boat
carries at least 2,000 bottles of phensidyl worth about tk 200,000
(about 500 U.S. dollars).  
</P>
