<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Enters New Era of Peace, Development: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has made
remarkable progress in peace and development during the past year,
according to Philippine President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation to be delivered in the
Presidential Palace tomorrow, Ramos said that the country is now
"politically stable and the Filipinos are more united than ever."
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement between the government and the Moro
National Liberation Front (MNLF), which was signed last September,
is a tribute to all Filipinos and the Philippines has entered a
new era of peace and development, the president added.
</P>
<P>
With respect to the rebel groups which consider themselves
outside the government-MNLF peace pact, Ramos said that the
government also opened venues for dialogue and conciliation.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF has so far been the only rebel group that struck a
peace deal with the government. The Moro Islamic Liberation Front,
the Abu Sayyaf extremists group and other insurgency groups in the
country all oppose the peace accord between the government and the
MNLF.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also said that there is now a widespread consensus that
the country has entered an era of sustained growth, with all the
leading economic indicators pointing to a strong and continued
growth.
</P>
<P>
He said the Philippines reached a gross national product growth
of 7.1 percent for the first three quarters of 1996, making the
country one of the fastest growing economies in Asia last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate was at a low of 8.7 percent for the first 11
months of last year while the average unemployment rate for the
first three quarters fell to 8.9 percent, the lowest since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The country also had a good performance in exports with a
growth of 16.7 percent for the first 10 months. Its gross
international reserves reached a record high of 11.6 billion U.S.
dollars as of November.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said although these accomplishments rekindled greater
hope and optimism for the future, the country is facing some major
challenges.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the country is being challenged by continuity
and durability of its reforms, alleviation of mass poverty and the
strengthening of law and order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
