<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup: Reactions to Hebron Shooting Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today sharply condemned this morning's shooting
incident carried out by an Israeli soldier in downtown Hebron.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest Israel Radio report, which could not be
confirmed by either the Israeli Government Press Office or the
Army's spokesman, six Palestinians were wounded, and one of them
seriously, during today's shooting attack.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian's Jerusalem Media and Communications
Center, contacted by phone, said that plus the six wounded by
gunshots five other Palestinian shoppers were beaten and injured
by Israeli soldiers shortly after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Radio report said that Noam Friedman, 19, an
Orthodox resident of Ma'aleh Adumim, who is in his three-year
mandatory  military service, but not posted in Hebron, carried
out the attack by himself.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that Friedman came to Hebron early this
morning, and had been wondering around the city, apparently
looking for a better position to carry out his plan, before he
entered the vegetable market and started shooting.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports said one Palestinian was killed at the scene,
and at least nine others were wounded, three of them seriously,
before three Israeli soldiers, posted in Hebron, jumped to
Friedman and subdued him.
</P>
<P>
He later admitted to investigators that he came to the Hebron
area with the premeditated intention of carrying out this attack,
in his own words, "to stop the Hebron accords that are planned to
be signed."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he would not allow today's attack, which
he termed as "a criminal act," to hold up the signing of an
agreement on the Israeli army's redeployment in the West Bank
town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who was meeting with US special Middle East
coordinator Dennis Ross in Jerusalem this morning, called
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat in front
of Ross and made the condemnation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli premier also called on the Palestinians
to show restraints and responsibility in the wake of the shooting
attack.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Arafat urged the Israelis to go ahead with the
implementation of the Oslo peace accords, while instructed
Palestinian Security forces to help the Israelis to keep calm in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Prevention forces in
the West Bank, visited the scene today and said that the shooting
incident approved that it was the Palestinians who were in
danger.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian negotiator Sa'eb Erekat has expressed his
"outrage," and called on Netanyahu to move ahead with the Hebron
talks and to stick to the Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that if Netanyahu "believes the settlers and the
Arabs can live next to one another with fences, he is
wrong. Today, we see once again the settlers must be removed
(from Hebron)."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, accompanied by
Israeli army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, also visited the
scene and called on both Israeli and Palestinian residents in
Hebron to maintain calm.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who is traveling to Gaza to meet with Arafat at this
hour, has issued a statement on behalf of US President Bill
Clinton and Secretary of State Warren Christopher, denouncing the
shooting attack.
</P>
<P>
Labor member of the Knesset (parliament) Ehud Barak said
shooting of innocent people "hurts Israel's interest."
</P>
<P>
Yossi Beilin, also from the Labor Party and one of the
architects of the Oslo peace accords, warned that further delay in
signing the Hebron redeployment accord would lead to further
violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, right-wing Likud member Ze'ev Begin, who opposes
the Hebron redeployment, also denounced the wounding of innocent
people, but added it should not pressure Israel into the
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Although both Israel and the Palestinians vowed to conclude
the Hebron deal as soon as possible, the Palestinians suspended
this morning's scheduled talks for consultation after the Hebron
shooting attack.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear yet whether a summit meeting between Netanyahu
and Arafat will still take place today, as previously expected,
to initial the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israel Radio quoted Ross as saying that the two sides
are stilling working on the Hebron redeployment deal, and that he
hoped the agreement "will be reached soon."
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian officials had said that Netanyahu and
Arafat would probably meet today at the Erez checkpoint between
Israel and the Gaza Strip, as negotiators iron out the final
issues.
</P>
<P>
However, so far the two sides apparently have failed to reach
an agreement on Israel's further redeployment in the West Bank
after Hebron, and on the release of Palestinian prisoners from
Israeli prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
