<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Tops World Traffic Safety League: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Sweden has the best traffic
safety record in the world, the "Dagens Nyheter" daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 565 people died in traffic accidents in the country,
the lowest in the world when set against the number of vehicles on
the road. There are four million vehicles registered in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
However, Claes Tingv All, the official in charge of traffic
safety in Sweden's Highway Bureau, stressed that 565 deaths mean
565 tragedies, so this was nothing to be proud of.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents soared in Sweden in the mid-1960s, with some
1,300 deaths annually. But the number has fallen steadily since
1989 when traffic-related deaths dropped to 904.
</P>
<P>
The Highway Bureau attributes the drop to improved traffic
safety measures, including better quality vehicles, better roads
and reducing the number of drivers under 18 years of age. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
