<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia to Carry Out New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia will carry out
a new fiscal budget for 1997 with an emphasis on manpower
training, gaining competence in the public sector and further
promoting the private sector.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, the world's biggest oil producer and
exporter, announced the new budget last Tuesday, saying that the
budget aimed to continue his country's development drive and
achieve a strong and balanced economy.
</P>
<P>
He added the new budget emphasized on three pivotal
points: development and training of Saudi manpower and increasing
employment, achieving competence in both public and private
sectors, and consolidating the role of the private sector in the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The budget projects revenues of 164 billion Saudi Riyals
(43.73 billion U.S. dollars), up 32.5 billion Riyals (8.67
billion dollars) from last year. And an expenditure stands at 181
billion Riyals (48.27 billion dollars), an increase of 31 billion
Riyals (8.27 billion dollars) over the last budget.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit will be up to 17 billion Riyals (4.5
billion dollars), or 3 percent below the level of 4.9
billion dollars in 1996. Saudi Finance and National Economy
Ministry has been authorized to borrow to offset the deficit,
Saudi official sources said.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd considered the new budget as "an important step
toward achieving balance and reaffirming the Kingdom's economic
strength."
</P>
<P>
He said Saudi economic "growth bas reached 8.6 percent at
current rates compared with the 4.3 percent growth rate in 1995,"
achieving a positive rise for the third consecutive year in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that as Saudi Arabia enters the third year of its
sixth Five-Year-Plan, he is optimistic that the target of the
plan designed to "achieve qualitative and speedy progress to
ensure high standard of social security and economic prosperity"
will be reached.
</P>
<P>
Economic sources said the oil price rise encouraged the state
to push up overall 1977 spending by 8,27 billion U.S. dollars
compared with that of 1996. They expected that the oil price
would remain stable at the same level seen in the last quarter of
1996. The current five-year plan targeted the creation of
120,000 jobs totally for the local workforce over the five years.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, this is possible through expanding
activities of both the government and private sectors as well as
replacing expatriate workforce with the indigenous.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Finance Ministry said in a statement that 11 billion
dollars or 22 percent of the new budget is earmarked for
workforce training.
</P>
<P>
Health and social service spending rates second for 4.7
billion dollars or 9 percent of the new budget.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.33 billion dollars has been set for state funds
on industrial, agricultural and real estate projects.
</P>
<P>
According to the same statement, the balance of payments
improved notably in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus stood at 186 million dollars
compared with 5.3 billion dollars deficit in 1995 as a result of
the rise in oil prices, despite the fall in world prices of
petrochemicals and agricultural exports, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector's performance was also positive in 1996
with the financial position of banks standing at 93 billion
dollars last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970101.0136 </DOCNO>
