<HEADLINE> Australian PM Paints Hopeful Picture For 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today painted a hopeful and confident picture for his
country in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message, Howard said Australians had every
reason to look forward to 1997 with hope and confidence.
</P>
<P>
"Very low inflation, lower interest rates, more flexible labor
market conditions and substantial progress in cutting the budget
deficit all bode well for strong business investment and greater
consumer confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard pointed out that much of the government's economic
reform agenda had been achieved in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He named the waterfront, small business red tape, the Telstra
(telecommunication ltd.) sale and the National Heritage Trust
environmental agenda as reform priorities for the new year.
</P>
<P>
"We still have many blemishes, some of our fellow Australians
remain profoundly underprivileged living in or at the edge of
poverty. They continue to need our compassion and help. If we can
keep that balance, 1997 will be a very good year for Australia,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer called on
Australians to "be nice to our tourists" in his new year's
message.  
</P>
</TEXT>
