<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soldier Admits to Prevent Hebron Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli soldier who
carried out a shooting attack in downtown Hebron this morning
said that he came to prevent the implementation of Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Army Radio report, the soldier, Noam
Friedman, 19, an Orthodox resident of Ma'aleh Adumim, is in his
three-year mandatory military service, but was not posted in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that Friedman came to Hebron early this
morning, and had been wondering around the city, apparently
looking for a better position to carry out his plan, before he
entered the vegetable market and started shooting.
</P>
<P>
One Palestinian was killed at the scene, and at least nine
others were wounded, three of them seriously, before three
Israeli soldiers, posted in Hebron, jumped to subdue Friedman.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Friedman fired until the magazine of his
M-16 rifle was emptied.
</P>
<P>
He later admitted to investigators that he came to the Hebron
area with the premeditated intention of carrying out this attack,
in his own words, "to stop the Hebron accords that are planned to
be signed."
</P>
<P>
Riots have been reported near the Ali'ya Hospital in Hebron,
where the wounded Palestinians are being treated.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of Palestinian civilians are also heading
towards the hospital, Palestinian Radio said, many of them are
trying to donate blood to help the victims of the attack.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu immediately condemned
today's shooting incident in Hebron, and vowed to move ahead
with the planned signing of the Hebron Accord.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who was meeting with US special Middle East
coordinator Dennis Ross in Jerusalem, called Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat and made the pledge.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier said that the shooting attack was aimed at
stopping the planned Hebron redeployment, as well as the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu expressed his determination that he would not let
the incident destroy the Hebron agreement, which is currently
under intensive negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the incident, Palestinian Prevention forces
head in the West Bank Jibril Rajoub said that the shooting
incident approved that it was the Israelis who endangered the
security in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian negotiator Sa'eb Erekat has expressed
his outrage, and called on Netanyahu to move ahead with the
Hebron talks and to stick to the Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that if Netanyahu "believes the settlers and the
Arabs can live next to one another with fences, he is
wrong. Today, we see once again the settlers must be removed
(from Hebron)."
</P>
<P>
A curfew has been imposed on Hebron by the Israeli army, and
armored personnel carriers are reportedly being brought into
Hebron from nearby Kiryat Arba in order to prevent follow-up
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear yet whether a summit meeting between Netanyahu
and Arafat will still take place today, as previously expected,
to finalize the agreement on Israeli army's redeployment in Hebron
despite the shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israel Radio quoted US special Middle East
coordinator Dennis Ross as saying that the two sides are stilling
working on the Hebron redeployment deal, and that he hoped the
agreement "will be reached soon."
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian officials had said that Netanyahu and
Arafat would probably meet today at the Erez checkpoint between
Israel and the Gaza Strip, as negotiators iron out the final
issues.
</P>
<P>
However, so far the two sides apparently have failed to reach
an agreement on Israel's further redeployment in the West Bank
after Hebron, and on the release of Palestinian prisoners from
Israeli prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
