<HEADLINE> Citibank to Conduct Renminbi Business in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Citibank, one of the major
U.S. banks and largest ones in the world, will conduct Renminbi
(the Chinese currency) business in Pudong New Area (East
Shanghai).
</P>
<P>
An official of the bank's North Asia headquarters in Hong Kong
said Tuesday that Citibank will make Pudong its main branch in
Shanghai, and its original branch in Puxi (West Shanghai) a
subbranch according to the requirements in starting Renminbi
business.
</P>
<P>
Daisy Sham, vice-president of Corporate Communications of
Citibank North Asia Office, said that its Pudong branch will
provide Renminbi-denominated services to corporate customers who
are foreign-invested enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The branch is also engaged in foreign currency-denominated
services allowable under the prevailing codes for foreign banking
operations in China which include trade services, cash management
and foreign exchange products, lending and financial advisory
services, she said.
</P>
<P>
John Beeman, Citibank's Country Corporate Officer for China,
said, "We are excited about this market-opening move for Citibank
in China."
</P>
<P>
He said, "I am confident that the bank's role in China will
grow in the years ahead through our Pudong branch and with the
help and support of our global network which spans 98 countries
and regions."
</P>
<P>
With the latest addition of the Pudong branch, Citibank has the
 largest network among American banks on the Chinese mainland,
with branches in Beijing, Shanghai and Shenzhen, representative
offices in Guangzhou and Xiamen, a subbranch in Puxi and a head
office for the mainland in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
