<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Choose Between Peace, Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- In an angry reaction to the
Hebron shooting today, Palestinian senior negotiator Saeb Erekat
said that Israel must choose between settlement and peace.
</P>
<P>
In the terrorist shooting early this morning, an Israeli soldier
shot at Palestinians in a central Hebron market, killing one and
wounding nine others.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that once again the incident proved that Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu was wrong in saying that he
could make peace with the Palestinians while expanding Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
"We want to tell the Israeli government once again that the
choice is yours: peace or settlement, you can't have both," he
told the U.S. television network CNN.
</P>
<P>
He prodded Netanyahu to "make up his mind" and to take genuine
efforts to push forward the peace process. He said that
settlements and terrorism should "belong to the past."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Erekat said that the peace process should
not be affected by today's incident, adding the talks on Israeli
troop withdrawal from Hebron would proceed as usual.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the shooting, Netanyahu telephoned
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to express his regrets over the
incident and sympathy for the victims, Netanyahu's senior adviser
Dore Gold said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu condemned any terrorist acts and reiterated his
determination to continue the peace process with the Palestinian
Authority (PA), Gold added.
</P>
<P>
Before today's incident, there had long been speculation about
plans by extremists on both sides to sabotage the upcoming Hebron
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The incident has apparently further shadowed the signing of an
impending Hebron agreement, which was expected to be initialled
today at a possible summit between Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that the Hebron talks would continue today, but he
refused to speculate on the timing of signing the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
