<HEADLINE> 400 Ugandan Rebels Retreat into Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 1 (xinhua) -- Over 400 rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA) have retreated from Uganda into Sudan,
reported the local daily ''the Monitor'' today.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are alleged to be withdrawing to avoid the
much-hyped offensive to be launched by the government army during
the dry season, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Shaban Bantariza, the public relation officer of the
government troops in the north, was quoted as saying that it is
possible for the rebels to retreat into Sudan on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
In November alone, some 500 IRA rebels had withdrawn to Sudan,
he revealed.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1987 the IRA has troops of some 2,000 men
currently.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kony, the IRA leader, threatened last September that
the IRA would abduct 10,000 Ugandans into Sudan for military
training. Its final goal is to create a multi-party country in
Uganda headed by Kony.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Sudan provided the IRA with arms to
enable them to cope with Sudanese rebels in south Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
