<HEADLINE> Report: Netanyahu, Arafat May Not Meet Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Meeting between Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat appeared unlikely to take place today,
according to an Israel Radio report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted U.S. special Middle East coordinator Dennis
Ross as saying that the two sides are still working on the Hebron
redeployment deal, and that he hoped the agreement will be
reached soon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian officials said earlier that Netanyahu
and Arafat would probably meet today at the Erez checkpoint
between Israel and the Gaza Strip after negotiators iron out the
final issues.
</P>
<P>
However, so far the two sides have apparently failed to reach
an agreement on Israel's further redeployment in the West Bank
after Hebron, and on the release of Palestinian detainees from
Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said earlier this morning he was still uncertain if
he would meet with Arafat today to initial an accord on Hebron,
adding he would not sign any agreement concerning Hebron until he
was absolutely sure that security provisions for the Jewish
community there will meet Israel's standard.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier said that it would be decided later in the
day if the two leaders will meet today to close the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Arafat and his deputy Abu Mazen stated they
were ready to meet with Netanyahu to discuss the Hebron
redeployment accord.
</P>
<P>
However, they also said that there was still a great deal of
work concerning subsequent stages of the Oslo Accords and a
timetable for further Israeli troop redeployment from the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
