<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Down, Exports Up in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania saw apparent
declines of the inflation rate and importing, while its national
revenue and exports shoot up at double-digit rates at the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Tanzania (BOT) said in its monthly economic review
issued Tuesday that the inflation rate fell to 16.2 percent in
November and possibly to 15 percent in December, compared with
18.8 percent in October, and the record 21.8 percent in December
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Such a decrease was a result of the slight drop of food prices
and the tightened monetary policies the government has been
pursuing especially on the cash-budget system, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The BOT, the central bank of the eastern African country, also
predicted the inflation rate might drop to 10 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tanzania's state revenue reached some 372 million
U.S. dollars in the first four months of 1996-1997 fiscal year,
about 10 percent above the set target.
</P>
<P>
The exports of the country also hit 661.2 million dollars
between January and November in 1996, up 12 percent over the same
period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Much of this improvement is due to the increase in export
volumes as well as general improvement in export prices," the BOT
report said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's imports dropped by 10 percent to 1.27 billion
dollars from January to November, down from 1.41 billion dollars
during the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Imported capital goods, intermediate and consumer items have
sharply declined, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
