<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Shooting Incident in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu condemned today's shooting incident in
Hebron during which one Palestinian was killed and nine others
were wounded, Israel Army Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who is currently meeting with U.S. special Middle
East coordinator Dennis Ross in Jerusalem, called Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat and made the
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier said that the shooting attack was aimed at
stopping the planned Hebron redeployment as well as the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu expressed his determination not to let the incident
destroy the Hebron agreement, which is currently under intensive
negotiations between Israeli and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
An initial report said that an Israeli soldier entered the
vegetable market in central Hebron with his M-16 rifle and
suddenly opened fire on Palestinians in the market.
</P>
<P>
One Palestinian was killed at the scene, and the wounded were
rushed to a nearby hospital outside Hebron, where doctors said two
of the wounded were in serious conditions, said the report.
</P>
<P>
A doctor from the hospital told Army Radio that three out of
the nine were badly wounded and one of them was still in a very
serious condition at this hour.
</P>
<P>
The soldier was caught by Israeli troops stationed in
Hebron, and Israel Radio said that he apparently came from
Ma'aleh Adomim, a Jewish settlement north of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted army sources as saying that the soldier
claimed that he was chasing and shooting Palestinians who threw
stones at him.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the incident, Jibril Rajoub, head of the
Palestinian Prevention Forces in the West Bank, said that the
shooting incident approved that it was the Israelis who posed a
danger to the security in Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
