<HEADLINE> PKK Raid Radio Station in Southeast Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) attacked a Turk-Telekom radio-link
station in southeastern Turkey on the new year eve.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News said today that no casualties
were reported in the attack in Ergani district of Diyarbakir.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted security officials as saying that
operations were underway in the region to capture the PKK
militants.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces have killed 13,255 PKK militants,
wounded 244 and captured about 2,000 in the past ten years,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,900 soldiers of the security forces have been also
killed in clashes with the militant group.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the security forces have seized large quantities
of munition and weapons.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the security forces wiped out 2,782 PKK rebels,
injured 36 and captured about 320 in the military operations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
More than 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed since August 1984 when the
PKK started separatist war in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
