<HEADLINE> 7 Fires Hit Philippine Capital on New Year's Eve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- At least seven fires hit the
Philippine capital of Manila on the New Year's eve and the biggest
one gutted the Logistics Command of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines (AFP), the Bureau of Fire Protection reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
Two soldiers were injured in the blaze that razed the
two-storey administration building of the logistics command
located inside the compound of the AFP at Camp Aguinaldo in the
capital, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Military officials said the fire, which broke out at about
20:15 (12:15 GMT), was due to faulty electrical wiring.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, the supply depot was spared by the fire.
</P>
<P>
At least six other fires broke out later in the city and the
amount of damage was not immediately known, the Fire Protection
Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau did say what had caused the fires but analysts
attributed the incidents to the explosion of firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Manila residents went out into the streets last
night, exploding firecrackers, throwing sparklers, and spraying
multi-colored fireworks rays into the sky.
</P>
<P>
As the clock moved closer to the midnight, bursts of
firecrackers were all over Manila. The explosions continued up to
early this morning. Many people were reportedly injured by the
firecrackers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
