<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-01 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fatah Marks Anniversary of Anti-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With fireworks and street
gatherings, Fatah, the largest faction of the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO), celebrated today the 32nd
anniversary of its anti-Israeli struggle.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the new year, tens of thousands of Palestinians
held demonstrations in the West Bank and Gaza Strip to show their
support to Palestinian Authority (PA) President Yasser Arafat,
who founded the Fatah Movement 38 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza, thousands of people took to the street in a show of
support for Arafat and his efforts to make peace with Israel. Some
demonstrators held placards reading "Fatah can make war and peace
in victory and sacrifices" and "We promise to keep the guns held
high along the olive branches."
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank city of Ramallah, fireworks display was held
to mark the group's 32nd anniversary, followed by a torch-light
procession joined by thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities erected a flashing orange neon sign on
top of a building in the city center, which says "Call all our
people who have weapons and say long live Fatah."
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 Palestinian policemen held a player ceremony
before the Palestinian flag in Jericho, the first West Bank town
that came under Palestinian autonomy in 1994 under the
Israeli-Palestinian peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Last year, with Fatah Day coming while the PA took charge of
six West Bank towns, celebrations could not be prepared in
time. So this year's anniversary was marked on a large scale to
salute Arafat's leadership and "the struggle for an independent
Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
Fatah was founded in 1959 in Kuwait where Arafat, a civil
engineer, established a construction company, but its existence
is traditionally dated from January 1, 1965 when a cell of the
organization launched the first attack against Israel's
occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
