<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Against Sectarian Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim has
cautioned political party leaders in Africa against antagonizing
the people to meet their own political aspirations.
</P>
<P>
Salim, a Zanzibari, who is in Zanzibar for Christmas and News
Year holidays, met Zanzibar President Salmin Amour at State House
in the town of Zanzibar on Tuesday and and said political party
leaders should discourage the sowing of seeds of hatred and
division.
</P>
<P>
He added that unity is the pillar of stability.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief also said that political parties in Africa
should build a culture of respecting their countries
constitutions to avoid unnecessary friction and conflicts,
according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Without mentioning any political party, Salim underscored the
need for parties to accept election results instead of waging war
on the outcome of the polls.
</P>
<P>
Salim emphasised that unless African countries cooperate and
utilize fully resources available within the continent, living
standards would continue declining.
</P>
<P>
He discouraged the habit by African nations of depending on
donor support to bail them out of economic quagmire, insisting
that the countries should stand up together and look for a
solution to their common snags.
</P>
<P>
The Isles president, on his part, assured the OAU chief that
Zanzibar's situation is calm and requested him to persuade donors
to support development projects.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the OAU secretary General met the Isles Chief
Minister Mohammed Ghari Bilal for discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
