<HEADLINE> Abacha Advocates French as Nigeria's 2nd National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State, General
Sani Abacha said he advocates French as the country's second
national language after English.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks on Tuesday while receiving an interim
report of the Committee on the Future of Higher Education headed
by Etsu Nupe.
</P>
<P>
Abacha said that, given the imperativeness of international
relations, Nigeria should consider becoming an official bilingual
country as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Nigeria is surrounded by French-speaking
countries on all sides, Niger to the north, Benin to west, Chad
and Cameroun to the east.
</P>
<P>
Closer cooperation with these neighbors, to be fostered by
linguistic affinity, would enhance social and economic benefits
for all concerned, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha claimed that the lack of communication has eroded the
common values and aspirations of Nigeria and its French-speaking
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He also called on these neighbors to also learn to speak
English for political, social and economic benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
