<HEADLINE> Israeli Knesset Passes 1997 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Knesset (Israel's
parliament) today approved the 1997 budget bill totaling 190
billion shekels (some 60 billion US dollars) by a vote of 60-42.
</P>
<P>
The vote in the third and final reading took place at 04:45 am
local time (0245GMT), one hour before the deadline for the bill
to be passed into law.
</P>
<P>
The ratification came after a Marathon debate throughout the
day in the Knesset, during which some coalition members of the
government threatened to vote against the budget.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, the Knesset approved the Economic
Arrangements Law, which gave the green line to the government's
planned 7.2 billion shekel (some 2.4 billion US dollars) deficit
reduction.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu said after voting that the
passage of the budget bill proved his government knows how to take
difficult steps.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held a series of meetings with the various coalition
factions during the day to give them a tongue-lashing on the need
to present a unified front during voting.
</P>
<P>
He postponed a summit meeting with Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat Tuesday to close the Hebron
redeployment agreement, so as to make sure that the budget would
be passed.
</P>
<P>
However, the government is still facing a 270-million-shekel
(some 90 million US dollars) hole due to its failure to pass a
measure on Monday to eliminate the half tax credit given married
working women. The Treasury said it has still not decided how to
fill this hole.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the government's failure on the half tax
credit, the key measures originally proposed by the Treasury in
the Arrangements Law -- cuts in child allowances, institution of
payments for doctors' visits and a hike in copayments for
medicine -- were withdrawn due to pressure from coalition members
in the Knesset Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
They were replaced with a series of tax hikes, despite
Netanyahu's repeated promises not to raise taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
