<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Makes Progress towards Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
made progress towards resettlement and rehabilitation in the
war-torn Jaffna peninsula, according to official sources here
today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that over 412,900 civilians have been
resettled in Jaffna peninsula. Out of the 425 schools in the area,
409 with 96,800 students began classes.
</P>
<P>
With normalcy returning to Jaffna city, 69,000 Identity cards
have been issued and it is expected that the rest will be issued
within the next three months, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
State institutions such as building material corporation,
telecommunications, banks and the Cooperative Wholesale
Establishment are functioning well in the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The office building of the Jaffna Municipal Council is being
renovated and the drainage system is being reconstructed with aid
from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of roads is also underway.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna peninsula, once the stronghold of the Tamil rebels, was
recaptured by the government troops in May last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
