<HEADLINE> Zambia's Non-Traditional Exports Perform Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's non-traditional exports
did very well on the international market in 1996 and its
earnings are expected to exceed the 15 percent increase projected
for the year.
</P>
<P>
This is revealed by Mwansa Musonda, Executive Director of the
Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) in a radio interview with Zambia
National Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports earned the country 216 million U.S.
Dollars in 1995, which are expected to reach 250 million US
Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Musonda attributed the improved performance to the textile,
agricultural and floral cultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
The textile sector has been earning an average of 3.5 million
US Dollars per month mostly from lint and yarn which are expected
to bring in about 14 million Dollars by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural produce such as soya beans and maize are on high
demand but there is need for mass production in order to satisfy
the rising demand in the export market.
</P>
<P>
Floral cultural products in form of cut flowers are another
export whose demand has been increasing in the European market.
</P>
<P>
Musonda said his organization is working flat out to ensure
that non-traditional exports become more popular in both
potential and target markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
