<HEADLINE> 200 Begging Children Saved on Harare Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 200 street children
have been saved from life on Harare's streets and given a home
while 31 of them will be starting school this year as the city
council tackles problems of begging.
</P>
<P>
The 31 children, aged between 11 and 16 years, were rounded up
on Harare's streets and sent to Mbuya Nehanda training center in
Mashonaland East Province. They have all expressed a wish to go
back to school.
</P>
<P>
Attempts will be made to send all the children to school this
year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an end of year party hosted for the children,
Mayor of capital Harare Solomon Tawengwa yesterday said that the
street kids problem would be the number one priority of the
Christmas cheer fund.
</P>
<P>
He said money would be given to the institution for the
education of the children.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said he was in the process of negotiating with
companies in the private sector to offer these youngsters jobs
after giving them a bit of training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
