<HEADLINE> Chissano Calls for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has put both the first local autonomous elections and
the population census at high agenda of the government in 1997,
the Noticiais newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
When delivering a New-Year address Tuesday, Chissano
reiterated that the elections, scheduled for November, "will not
include all of the towns, villages or residential areas" in the
once war-torn southern African country.
</P>
<P>
However, the poll will be conducive to the promotion of
national unity, the further economic and social reconstruction
and the improvement of Mozambicans' living standard, Chissano
noted.
</P>
<P>
He called for administrative reforms in 1997 so as to enhance
the efficiency and transparency of the governmental bodies.
</P>
<P>
With the development of national harmony and democracy,
Mozambique also succeeded in curbing inflation and decreasing
foreign debts and its gross domestic product went up six percent
in 1996, said Chissano.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chissano called on all the Mozambicans to
maintain "national unity" when fighting crimes and defending
social moral values. 
</P>
</TEXT>
