<HEADLINE> Thai PM Declares 1997 Year of Savings for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has declared 1997 "the year of savings" in line with
the government's policy to promote savings and ease the current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
In a new year message, available today, Chavalit urged the
public and private sectors and the people to spend money prudently
throughout this year.
</P>
<P>
"Let us tighten our belts. We must be thrifty and austere," he
said, adding "let's cut unnecessary spending, especially overseas
spending, to reduce the current trade deficit."
</P>
<P>
Thailand's current account deficit in 1996 was expected to be
at a high 8.2 percent of gross domestic product and the government
aimed to reduce it to 7.9 percent in the new year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also urged the people to cooperate with the
government in the face of economic and social problems.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports in 1996 recorded a near-zero growth, as
against a 24-percent increase in 1995. The abrupt growth drop had
caused much worry for the Thai economy in the new year.
</P>
<P>
In the social field, the prime minister said that the
administration will push for improvement and effective enforcement
of laws and regulations to tackle social problems, including
drugs, prostitution, child labor, crime and aids.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
