<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Boutros Boutros-Ghali on Tuesday bid farewell
to the United Nations, whose term as the head of the world body
terminates on December 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council Tuesday decided to
maintain economic sanctions against Iraq at its 35th review of the
sanctions, Council President Francesco Paolo Fulci of Italy said.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African President Nelson Mandela said on
the new year's eve that his government will speed up national
reconstruction in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam Wednesday
stressed the need for reconciliation between the two countries of
the Korean Peninsula and expressed his hope for improved
inter-Korean relations in 1997.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peruvian rebels occupying the residence of the Japanese
ambassador here released two more hostages Tuesday, but they were
still holding 81 hostages in the compound.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- One person was killed and 29 others injured in a
series of chain-reaction crashes on Tuesday, which involved at
least 70 vehicles in dense fog on an interstate highway in New
Orleans, the United States. 
</P>
