<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Takes Steps to Curb Illegal Gold Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is lossing up to 50
million U.S. Dollars worth of gold annually through illegal
exports, prompting the government to introduce experimental
measures to curb the problem, the Daily Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mines Deputy Minister Zenzo Nsimbi told the Herald that the
government had introduced an experimental permit system under
which designated agents would buy gold from small-scale producers
and sell to the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
At present, it is difficult for small-scale producers to sell
gold of less than 50 grams to the Central Bank, forcing them to
find alternative markets for their products, thereby falling prey
to illegal exporters, the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
''We are worried about the illegal sale of gold, mainly to
South Africa. the government has since decided to take up this
licensing thing. We will be making a maximized month to month
assessment to see whether we are making any impact,'' he said,
adding that the permits would be issued this month.
</P>
<P>
A private mining consultant from Harare John Hollaway said it
was estimated there are about 80,000 illegal gold panners in
Zimbabwe and these account for about four tons of the 24 tons
produced annually the country.
</P>
<P>
This means that Zimbabwe may loss between 25 and 50 million
U.S. Dollars worth of gold annually through illegal exports.
</P>
<P>
Hollaway said because of the regulations regarding the amount
of gold that could be sold to the Central Bank, most panners sold
their gold to unlicensed dealers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
