<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Criticises Male Colleagues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Olympic gold medal winner
Lindsay Davenport of the United States said on Wednesday that
men's tennis players should place more importance on the Olympics
and not treat the sport a bridge to make money.
</P>
<P>
"I think the Olympics were a lot more important to the women
this year," Davenport said. "It was disappointing on the men's
side that more of them didn't take it more seriously."
</P>
<P>
"Not everything to do with tennis revolves around making money,
some of it is just representing your country and being with some
of the greatest athletes in the world, " she said.
</P>
<P>
Davenport was speaking at White City, where she was practising
just hours after arriving in the country for the Sydney
International, which starts on Sunday, and the Australian Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
